00:00:25.440 --> 00:00:26.823
PROFESSOR: OK, good afternoon.

00:00:30.140 --> 00:00:34.820
So this week we talk
about quantum gases,

00:00:34.820 --> 00:00:37.930
ultra-cold atomic gases.

00:00:37.930 --> 00:00:43.080
And sure, they're ideal Bose
gases, ideal Fermi gases,

00:00:43.080 --> 00:00:45.360
but I will spend one
or two minutes on each,

00:00:45.360 --> 00:00:47.740
because that's exactly solvable.

00:00:47.740 --> 00:00:49.250
It's in all the textbooks.

00:00:49.250 --> 00:00:51.560
That's simple.

00:00:51.560 --> 00:00:55.700
Quantum gases become interesting
because of interactions.

00:00:55.700 --> 00:00:58.610
And in my lecture today
and my last lecture

00:00:58.610 --> 00:01:01.070
I want to introduce you
to Bose gases and Fermi

00:01:01.070 --> 00:01:03.110
gases with inter actions.

00:01:03.110 --> 00:01:07.180
And they both turn superfluid,
and the superfluid properties

00:01:07.180 --> 00:01:10.800
are determined by the
interactions between the atoms.

00:01:10.800 --> 00:01:15.110
So the purpose of those
lectures is number one,

00:01:15.110 --> 00:01:17.740
to acquaint to you with
important phenomena

00:01:17.740 --> 00:01:21.690
in cold gases-- superfluidity,
superfluidity in lattices,

00:01:21.690 --> 00:01:28.090
superfluidity just in
free gas, in a normal gas

00:01:28.090 --> 00:01:31.270
without lattice, and
superfluidity of fermions.

00:01:31.270 --> 00:01:33.090
But at the same
time, I also want

00:01:33.090 --> 00:01:36.470
to have sort of a theme for you
how we deal with interactions.

00:01:36.470 --> 00:01:43.110
And that kind of theme
is how theoretically we

00:01:43.110 --> 00:01:46.400
reduce unsolvable
Hamiltonians to Hamiltonians

00:01:46.400 --> 00:01:47.850
which can be solved.

00:01:47.850 --> 00:01:50.170
And you will see that
actually appearing

00:01:50.170 --> 00:01:55.240
in different situations
with similarities,

00:01:55.240 --> 00:01:57.220
but important differences.

00:01:57.220 --> 00:01:59.110
So just to remind
you, we started out

00:01:59.110 --> 00:02:03.210
with the interacting Bose
gas in a homogeneous system.

00:02:03.210 --> 00:02:05.615
We have a very general
way to describe

00:02:05.615 --> 00:02:09.250
scattering two particles with
initial momentum disappear

00:02:09.250 --> 00:02:11.760
and two particles
with momenta appear.

00:02:11.760 --> 00:02:14.320
This is a scattering event.

00:02:14.320 --> 00:02:17.750
Now this means we have products
of four operators, which

00:02:17.750 --> 00:02:19.760
is very difficult to solve.

00:02:19.760 --> 00:02:23.690
And the Bogoliubov approximation
which we discussed on Monday

00:02:23.690 --> 00:02:28.420
replaces the operator for
the condensate for the zero

00:02:28.420 --> 00:02:33.900
momentum state with a Z number,
saying that N 0, N 0 plus 1

00:02:33.900 --> 00:02:36.180
is the same-- a little
bit waving your hands.

00:02:36.180 --> 00:02:39.410
But it's also you can say
the macroscopic limit when

00:02:39.410 --> 00:02:42.250
we have a photon field
with many, many photons,

00:02:42.250 --> 00:02:44.650
we can use a Z number
in our Hamiltonian

00:02:44.650 --> 00:02:46.650
to describe the electric field.

00:02:46.650 --> 00:02:48.520
So that's the same spirit.

00:02:48.520 --> 00:02:50.470
So maybe I should emphasize it.

00:02:50.470 --> 00:02:52.090
This is for atoms.

00:02:52.090 --> 00:02:56.121
What you're used to do with
photons for your whole life.

00:02:56.121 --> 00:02:56.620
OK.

00:02:56.620 --> 00:02:59.060
With that we have
transformed the Hamiltonian

00:02:59.060 --> 00:03:01.740
into a bilinear expression.

00:03:01.740 --> 00:03:04.920
And so at the moment your
bilinear expression--

00:03:04.920 --> 00:03:06.720
you do a Bogoliubov
transformation.

00:03:06.720 --> 00:03:12.110
You simply diagonalize it by
finding a new set operators

00:03:12.110 --> 00:03:16.320
where the cross term
between a and b or between a

00:03:16.320 --> 00:03:20.240
of k and a of minus k disappear.

00:03:20.240 --> 00:03:23.340
And then you've solved it.

00:03:23.340 --> 00:03:28.350
And this is what we arrived at
at the end of the last lecture.

00:03:28.350 --> 00:03:30.700
With those
approximations, we have

00:03:30.700 --> 00:03:32.250
diagonalized the Hamiltonian.

00:03:32.250 --> 00:03:35.650
Our Hamiltonian is now, you
can say harmonic oscillator

00:03:35.650 --> 00:03:38.040
Hamiltonian, or
you can see it has

00:03:38.040 --> 00:03:42.430
become a gas of non-interacting
quasi particles.

00:03:42.430 --> 00:03:45.620
Each of those operators
creates a quasi particle,

00:03:45.620 --> 00:03:48.360
and the quasi particle
energy is U of k.

00:03:48.360 --> 00:03:50.880
And I explained to
you that as expected,

00:03:50.880 --> 00:03:54.070
the quasi particle
energy is simply

00:03:54.070 --> 00:03:57.710
particles with momentum
h-bar k for high momenta,

00:03:57.710 --> 00:04:00.460
because in high excitation
of Bose quantums

00:04:00.460 --> 00:04:02.000
it is a free particle.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:06.400
But a low-lying excitation
is affected in a major way

00:04:06.400 --> 00:04:07.880
by all of these
interactions with

00:04:07.880 --> 00:04:09.610
the Bose-Einstein condensate.

00:04:09.610 --> 00:04:12.880
And that turns the quadratic
dispersion relation

00:04:12.880 --> 00:04:15.350
into a linear one,
or you can say

00:04:15.350 --> 00:04:18.500
that turns the free particle
into a photon or something.

00:04:21.240 --> 00:04:22.890
So that's my review
of the last class.

00:04:22.890 --> 00:04:27.050
Are there any questions
before we go further?

00:04:27.050 --> 00:04:27.740
Colin.

00:04:27.740 --> 00:04:30.073
AUDIENCE: Does this require
low density and [INAUDIBLE],

00:04:30.073 --> 00:04:34.267
or one or the other?

00:04:34.267 --> 00:04:36.850
PROFESSOR: We come a little bit
later to that, but in the end,

00:04:36.850 --> 00:04:38.500
there is a small parameter.

00:04:38.500 --> 00:04:41.790
The small parameter will be N
a cubed-- the gas parameter--

00:04:41.790 --> 00:04:45.090
N, the density, a cubed,
the scattering length.

00:04:45.090 --> 00:04:48.960
It's usually the dimensionless
combination of the two

00:04:48.960 --> 00:04:51.940
which decides whether we are
in the weakly or strongly

00:04:51.940 --> 00:04:53.670
interacting limit.

00:04:53.670 --> 00:04:57.180
There is another assumption
which we have made here,

00:04:57.180 --> 00:05:00.560
but it's related to that-- as
you will see a few moments--

00:05:00.560 --> 00:05:03.010
that most of the are
in the condensate.

00:05:03.010 --> 00:05:04.620
We assumed N0 is peak.

00:05:04.620 --> 00:05:07.500
The condensate depletion-- the
number of atoms which are not

00:05:07.500 --> 00:05:10.630
in the condensate,
t equals 0 is small.

00:05:10.630 --> 00:05:13.520
But let me just
first show you-- I

00:05:13.520 --> 00:05:16.080
want to mix in
theory and experiment

00:05:16.080 --> 00:05:18.350
how sound can be observed.

00:05:18.350 --> 00:05:21.240
I should actually say this
experiment is sort of dear

00:05:21.240 --> 00:05:23.220
to my heart, because
at some point

00:05:23.220 --> 00:05:27.320
it clicked to me how the
new world of atomic physics

00:05:27.320 --> 00:05:29.550
connects with condensed
matter physics.

00:05:29.550 --> 00:05:32.950
Soon after we had realized
Bose-Einstein condensates,

00:05:32.950 --> 00:05:36.560
a famous condensed matter
theorist said hey, Wolfgang,

00:05:36.560 --> 00:05:37.849
you should now observe sound.

00:05:37.849 --> 00:05:38.640
Sound is important.

00:05:38.640 --> 00:05:41.580
Yeah, OK, but how do
you observe sound?

00:05:41.580 --> 00:05:44.150
You know, use a piezo
and just kick the system

00:05:44.150 --> 00:05:45.550
and create a sound wave.

00:05:45.550 --> 00:05:48.130
And I said, oh, gosh, this
guy doesn't know with that

00:05:48.130 --> 00:05:51.280
if you put anything in contact
with the quantum gases--

00:05:51.280 --> 00:05:53.540
a piezo-- the gases
will just stick to it.

00:05:53.540 --> 00:05:55.577
He has no idea
what our system is.

00:05:55.577 --> 00:05:57.785
But then I said wait a
moment-- we have to translate.

00:05:57.785 --> 00:05:59.820
He says use a piezo.

00:05:59.820 --> 00:06:01.100
Well, I have to translate.

00:06:01.100 --> 00:06:02.840
In atomic physics
how do we kick atoms?

00:06:02.840 --> 00:06:04.620
With a laser beam.

00:06:04.620 --> 00:06:06.720
And in that moment,
I had the idea

00:06:06.720 --> 00:06:09.110
that we can take a
Bose-Einstein condensate,

00:06:09.110 --> 00:06:12.970
suddenly switch on a blue
de-tuned repulsive laser beam.

00:06:12.970 --> 00:06:15.980
This will do exactly as a
piezo-- create a density

00:06:15.980 --> 00:06:18.630
perturbation, and then
the density perturbation

00:06:18.630 --> 00:06:21.600
will propagate with
the speed of sound.

00:06:21.600 --> 00:06:23.720
And that worked.

00:06:23.720 --> 00:06:28.030
That was just when Bose-Einstein
condensations were very fresh.

00:06:28.030 --> 00:06:30.910
One of the first
scientific experiments

00:06:30.910 --> 00:06:33.230
done-- we switch on
the laser and you

00:06:33.230 --> 00:06:36.520
see color-coded in red the
density perturbation which

00:06:36.520 --> 00:06:38.080
propagates out of it.

00:06:38.080 --> 00:06:41.580
And the slope of this line
is the speed of sound.

00:06:41.580 --> 00:06:44.090
And here we determined
the speed of sound

00:06:44.090 --> 00:06:47.380
as a function of density.

00:06:47.380 --> 00:06:50.840
So that's how phonons--
or at least how

00:06:50.840 --> 00:06:53.180
the speed of sound
and wave packets which

00:06:53.180 --> 00:06:56.750
propagate with the speed
of sound can be prepared.

00:06:56.750 --> 00:06:59.880
I come back to phonons
and collective excitations

00:06:59.880 --> 00:07:01.830
in a few moments.

00:07:01.830 --> 00:07:04.385
But let me first say
when we have diagonalized

00:07:04.385 --> 00:07:08.890
the Hamiltonian we know
everything we want to know.

00:07:08.890 --> 00:07:11.720
I just focused on the
quasi particle energies,

00:07:11.720 --> 00:07:15.330
but you also know the
ground-state energy.

00:07:15.330 --> 00:07:19.300
And actually here Colin,
you see that the corrections

00:07:19.300 --> 00:07:21.340
to the ground-state
energy scale with N

00:07:21.340 --> 00:07:25.070
a cubed, so this is really the
small parameter in this system.

00:07:25.070 --> 00:07:29.060
But we can also find out what is
the ground state wave function.

00:07:29.060 --> 00:07:32.880
And let me use it to introduce
an important concept to you

00:07:32.880 --> 00:07:35.940
called the quantum depletion.

00:07:35.940 --> 00:07:38.890
When you have two atoms in the
condensator at zero momentum

00:07:38.890 --> 00:07:43.510
and you switch on
the interactions,

00:07:43.510 --> 00:07:48.265
the delta function interaction
couples zero momentum state

00:07:48.265 --> 00:07:50.740
to higher momentum states.

00:07:50.740 --> 00:07:52.850
So therefore, the
effect of interactions

00:07:52.850 --> 00:07:56.840
is that the condensate is
not just at zero momentum.

00:07:56.840 --> 00:08:00.010
It has some probability,
or some admixture,

00:08:00.010 --> 00:08:02.000
of finite momentum states.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:03.120
This is the ground state.

00:08:03.120 --> 00:08:06.400
This is how the Hamiltonian
is diagonalized.

00:08:06.400 --> 00:08:08.385
So from the Bogoliubov
approximation,

00:08:08.385 --> 00:08:12.130
where we introduced
this V and U parameter

00:08:12.130 --> 00:08:14.890
to transfer from one
set of Bose operators

00:08:14.890 --> 00:08:17.150
to another set of
Bose operators,

00:08:17.150 --> 00:08:21.260
those coefficients
give us the population

00:08:21.260 --> 00:08:24.410
of those momentum states in the
[INAUDIBLE] of the condensate.

00:08:24.410 --> 00:08:28.310
So if I now ask, what is
the condensate fraction?

00:08:28.310 --> 00:08:31.070
What is the number of atoms
in the zero momentum states?

00:08:31.070 --> 00:08:34.669
It's all atoms, but those
who have finite momentum.

00:08:34.669 --> 00:08:39.330
And we find again the
small parameter N a cubed.

00:08:39.330 --> 00:08:42.190
Now this quantum
depletion allows me now

00:08:42.190 --> 00:08:46.280
to make a distinction
between the cold atomic gas

00:08:46.280 --> 00:08:49.440
condensates and
superfluid helium form.

00:08:49.440 --> 00:08:54.480
In cold atomic gas condensates,
this correction is about 1%.

00:08:54.480 --> 00:08:59.430
So therefore, I can say
with 99% probability,

00:08:59.430 --> 00:09:02.410
or with 99% weight,
the condensate,

00:09:02.410 --> 00:09:04.790
the many-body wave
function of the condensate

00:09:04.790 --> 00:09:08.200
is just the zero momentum
state to the power N.

00:09:08.200 --> 00:09:12.030
And this very complicated
admixture of correlation

00:09:12.030 --> 00:09:19.800
into the ideal gas wave function
is only 1% for alkali gases.

00:09:19.800 --> 00:09:23.160
But for liquid helium,
the condensate fraction--

00:09:23.160 --> 00:09:26.030
even at zero
temperature-- is only 10%.

00:09:26.030 --> 00:09:27.930
So when people use
neutron scattering--

00:09:27.930 --> 00:09:30.870
it would be a long story in
itself how this is done--

00:09:30.870 --> 00:09:33.850
but when they use neutron
scattering to analyze

00:09:33.850 --> 00:09:36.060
the liquid helium
at low temperature,

00:09:36.060 --> 00:09:39.640
and figure out what is the
fraction of atoms which

00:09:39.640 --> 00:09:43.370
have zero momentum,
they found 10%.

00:09:43.370 --> 00:09:45.700
The quantum depletion is 90%.

00:09:45.700 --> 00:09:48.150
But that's just the
difference between a quantum

00:09:48.150 --> 00:09:51.310
gas and a quantum liquid.

00:09:51.310 --> 00:09:54.880
And in the quantum liquid--
in liquid helium-- N

00:09:54.880 --> 00:09:56.915
a cubed is on the
order of unity.

00:09:59.590 --> 00:10:04.370
OK, I mentioned this
dispersion relation.

00:10:04.370 --> 00:10:06.920
These are sort of
quasi particles.

00:10:06.920 --> 00:10:08.820
And I at least
showed you how you

00:10:08.820 --> 00:10:12.260
can measure the slope of the
quasi particle dispersion

00:10:12.260 --> 00:10:15.000
relation by propagating
sound waves.

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:18.300
But let me now tell you how we
can observe quasi particles'

00:10:18.300 --> 00:10:22.290
elementary excitations directly.

00:10:22.290 --> 00:10:26.710
And this is actually simply
done by light scattering.

00:10:26.710 --> 00:10:32.940
If you scatter a photon,
and the scattered photon

00:10:32.940 --> 00:10:38.720
loses energy h-bar U. And
it is scattered at an angle.

00:10:38.720 --> 00:10:41.860
Therefore, it
transfers momentum q.

00:10:41.860 --> 00:10:44.910
These forces can
only happen if there

00:10:44.910 --> 00:10:52.510
is an elementary excitation
with momentum q and energy h U.

00:10:52.510 --> 00:10:55.280
So in other words,
on a photon basis,

00:10:55.280 --> 00:10:57.270
you can see photon
by photon, if you

00:10:57.270 --> 00:11:01.860
scatter a photon, the photon
transfers momentum and energy.

00:11:01.860 --> 00:11:05.290
The process can only happen if
you can form a quasiparticle

00:11:05.290 --> 00:11:07.680
with this momentum and energy.

00:11:07.680 --> 00:11:10.330
So since this is sort of the
direct way of mapping out

00:11:10.330 --> 00:11:12.320
whether the system
has the possibility

00:11:12.320 --> 00:11:19.744
to absorb momentum q and energy
h nu, this has sort of a name.

00:11:19.744 --> 00:11:22.160
The scattering probability is
called the dynamic structure

00:11:22.160 --> 00:11:22.660
factor.

00:11:22.660 --> 00:11:25.680
And the dynamic structure
factor is just an integral

00:11:25.680 --> 00:11:29.550
over all the possibilities
that a many-body system can

00:11:29.550 --> 00:11:32.690
absorb momentum and energy.

00:11:32.690 --> 00:11:38.730
Now there is one
nice feature which

00:11:38.730 --> 00:11:40.802
was introduced by
us at MIT, and that

00:11:40.802 --> 00:11:43.260
is if you're going to measure
the dynamic structure factor,

00:11:43.260 --> 00:11:44.926
often you do it with
neutron scattering.

00:11:44.926 --> 00:11:48.230
You scatter neutrons or x-rays
and they scatter spontaneously

00:11:48.230 --> 00:11:50.870
at an angle, and
you need a detector

00:11:50.870 --> 00:11:54.430
to detect the
scattered particles.

00:11:54.430 --> 00:11:58.470
But in our case, because
the gas is so dilute,

00:11:58.470 --> 00:12:00.670
the distance between
atoms is on the order

00:12:00.670 --> 00:12:02.240
of the optical wavelengths.

00:12:02.240 --> 00:12:03.350
We don't want neutrons.

00:12:03.350 --> 00:12:04.570
We don't want x-rays.

00:12:04.570 --> 00:12:07.690
We want photons, because
the wavelengths of photons

00:12:07.690 --> 00:12:09.850
is perfectly matched
to the properties,

00:12:09.850 --> 00:12:13.260
to momentum transfer and
such we need for our system.

00:12:13.260 --> 00:12:16.200
But photons-- we
have photon lasers.

00:12:16.200 --> 00:12:20.920
So instead of in a painstakingly
way analyzing the frequency

00:12:20.920 --> 00:12:23.140
and the momentum of
scattered photons,

00:12:23.140 --> 00:12:26.360
we don't do the spontaneous
scattering process.

00:12:26.360 --> 00:12:28.180
We do a stimulated process.

00:12:28.180 --> 00:12:31.425
We use two laser beams,
and we stimulate a photon

00:12:31.425 --> 00:12:34.320
to be scattered into
the other laser beam.

00:12:34.320 --> 00:12:37.490
And by having the two laser
beams at frequency difference

00:12:37.490 --> 00:12:40.690
delta omega, we're
really asking the system,

00:12:40.690 --> 00:12:43.580
are you ready to absorb
delta omega energy?

00:12:43.580 --> 00:12:46.330
If yes, then you
have a quasiparticle.

00:12:46.330 --> 00:12:50.090
So this is how we do
quasiparticle spectroscopy.

00:12:50.090 --> 00:12:52.820
And a few years
later, this method

00:12:52.820 --> 00:12:58.310
was defined by the
[INAUDIBLE] Institute.

00:12:58.310 --> 00:13:00.630
And what you see
here is they varied

00:13:00.630 --> 00:13:03.380
the angles between the
two laser beams, realized

00:13:03.380 --> 00:13:05.370
different momentum
transfer, and what

00:13:05.370 --> 00:13:09.190
you see is the low dispersion,
the linear dispersion

00:13:09.190 --> 00:13:11.200
relation for low
momenta, and then

00:13:11.200 --> 00:13:14.970
the quadratic part
at high momentum.

00:13:14.970 --> 00:13:19.340
So this is called
BEC spectroscopy.

00:13:19.340 --> 00:13:23.060
It's a variant, you can see,
of Raman spectroscopy where

00:13:23.060 --> 00:13:27.530
you go from a zero quasiparticle
state to a one quasiparticle

00:13:27.530 --> 00:13:30.830
state through a
simulated Raman process,

00:13:30.830 --> 00:13:33.875
and this is how the dispersion
relation is determined.

00:13:38.920 --> 00:13:43.820
OK so I've so far
dealt with aspects

00:13:43.820 --> 00:13:47.200
of a homogeneous Bose-Einstein
condensate where,

00:13:47.200 --> 00:13:49.250
of course, if you're
a homogeneous system,

00:13:49.250 --> 00:13:52.590
you formulate everything
in momentum space.

00:13:52.590 --> 00:13:55.090
But now we want to
deal with the situation

00:13:55.090 --> 00:13:58.640
that our condensates
are finite in size.

00:13:58.640 --> 00:14:02.990
And in addition, they're
usually in a harmonic oscillator

00:14:02.990 --> 00:14:08.020
potential, and therefore their
density is inhomogeneous.

00:14:08.020 --> 00:14:13.350
Let me start the discussion with
the inhomogeneous Bose-Einstein

00:14:13.350 --> 00:14:16.440
condensate by showing
again a picture which

00:14:16.440 --> 00:14:19.900
brings in some
memories of '90, '96.

00:14:19.900 --> 00:14:22.130
It was the first
time that we could

00:14:22.130 --> 00:14:24.850
see the Bose-Einstein
condensate in the trap.

00:14:24.850 --> 00:14:27.820
Before people have just
seen it by time of flight

00:14:27.820 --> 00:14:29.900
when it was pretty
much already destroyed

00:14:29.900 --> 00:14:32.040
or it was just flying out.

00:14:32.040 --> 00:14:35.980
But here we see the trapped
Bose-Einstein condensate

00:14:35.980 --> 00:14:37.870
and we could even
take multiple pictures

00:14:37.870 --> 00:14:39.280
of the same condensate.

00:14:39.280 --> 00:14:41.380
So you can see that
this was the first time

00:14:41.380 --> 00:14:43.080
that a condensate
was seen alive.

00:14:46.550 --> 00:14:49.260
What you see here is actually
the bimodal distribution.

00:14:49.260 --> 00:14:52.400
You see the condensate and
then due to speckled pattern,

00:14:52.400 --> 00:14:54.640
the Fermi cloud
looks fragmented,

00:14:54.640 --> 00:14:56.395
but this is just a
speckled pattern due

00:14:56.395 --> 00:14:58.400
to the signal to noise.

00:14:58.400 --> 00:15:01.740
But here you really see now--
not in ballistic expansion

00:15:01.740 --> 00:15:06.030
as I showed you on Monday--
but really insight to the size

00:15:06.030 --> 00:15:08.860
and shape of the condensate.

00:15:08.860 --> 00:15:11.380
OK, how do we describe it?

00:15:11.380 --> 00:15:15.920
Well, the message is pretty
much exactly the same way

00:15:15.920 --> 00:15:19.010
as we did with the Bogoliubov
approximation and such,

00:15:19.010 --> 00:15:20.970
but instead of in
momentum space,

00:15:20.970 --> 00:15:23.960
we do it now in position space.

00:15:23.960 --> 00:15:25.720
Actually, I have
to say this week,

00:15:25.720 --> 00:15:28.370
I go through a lot of material.

00:15:28.370 --> 00:15:30.960
But what I'm trying
is to give you

00:15:30.960 --> 00:15:33.780
sort of a spirited
and animated overview

00:15:33.780 --> 00:15:35.730
that you really know
what is important.

00:15:35.730 --> 00:15:38.260
Where is the same
concept appearing again

00:15:38.260 --> 00:15:40.300
in a different way.

00:15:40.300 --> 00:15:42.590
The details-- I've
posted, actually,

00:15:42.590 --> 00:15:44.687
the original
articles, references.

00:15:44.687 --> 00:15:46.270
Some of are school
notes, some of them

00:15:46.270 --> 00:15:48.490
written by myself
on the backside.

00:15:48.490 --> 00:15:51.180
So yes, it's a little
bit different character

00:15:51.180 --> 00:15:52.680
than other lectures.

00:15:52.680 --> 00:15:54.750
I want to show you
a lot of things,

00:15:54.750 --> 00:15:59.160
and put a special
emphasis on the ideas.

00:15:59.160 --> 00:16:01.850
OK, so in second
quantization, we

00:16:01.850 --> 00:16:05.270
are now using field operators
which create and annihilate

00:16:05.270 --> 00:16:09.460
particles at position R.
This is the single particle

00:16:09.460 --> 00:16:12.400
Hamiltonian-- kinetic
energy and potential energy.

00:16:12.400 --> 00:16:17.720
And our interaction term has
now, again, four operators--

00:16:17.720 --> 00:16:20.740
two interrelation operators,
two creation operators,

00:16:20.740 --> 00:16:24.460
but they're now formulated
in position space.

00:16:24.460 --> 00:16:27.730
We do exactly the same as we
did in the homogeneous gas.

00:16:27.730 --> 00:16:30.590
We assume the potential
is short range.

00:16:30.590 --> 00:16:33.130
That means delta function.

00:16:33.130 --> 00:16:35.040
And that means we
can get rid of one

00:16:35.040 --> 00:16:38.670
of the integrations
in r and r prime.

00:16:38.670 --> 00:16:44.430
But we still have product
of four operators.

00:16:44.430 --> 00:16:48.490
We can formally solve the
equation by writing down

00:16:48.490 --> 00:16:53.090
Heisenberg's situation for the
equation of motion for those

00:16:53.090 --> 00:16:56.620
field operators, but of
course this cannot be solved.

00:16:56.620 --> 00:17:00.090
Remember products are
four operators are hard.

00:17:00.090 --> 00:17:03.280
We have to reduce
it to two operators.

00:17:03.280 --> 00:17:07.829
And this is actually done by the
Bogoliubov approximation again.

00:17:07.829 --> 00:17:10.740
But it's done here
in the following way.

00:17:10.740 --> 00:17:16.390
Remember, in the momentum space
we replaced a0 and a0 dagger

00:17:16.390 --> 00:17:18.750
by the square root of a0.

00:17:18.750 --> 00:17:24.160
What we do here is we say this
is sort of a quantum field.

00:17:24.160 --> 00:17:31.010
And when we have a superfluid,
this field operator

00:17:31.010 --> 00:17:32.790
has an average value.

00:17:32.790 --> 00:17:36.580
It's actually the macroscopic
superfluid order parameter.

00:17:36.580 --> 00:17:40.720
So we replace the operator
by an average value

00:17:40.720 --> 00:17:43.860
which we assume is large,
because many, many particles

00:17:43.860 --> 00:17:47.110
are in the superfluid state.

00:17:47.110 --> 00:17:50.220
And then we have
fluctuations which are small.

00:17:50.220 --> 00:17:53.430
And what we will do is-- it's
pretty clear-- when it comes

00:17:53.430 --> 00:17:57.000
to the fluctuations, we will
neglect higher products--

00:17:57.000 --> 00:17:59.060
products of four
fluctuation operators.

00:17:59.060 --> 00:18:02.605
And we are down to C
numbers and, as you

00:18:02.605 --> 00:18:04.260
will see, two operators.

00:18:08.010 --> 00:18:09.960
We can-- and this is
even more dramatic--

00:18:09.960 --> 00:18:11.850
it wouldn't make sense
in momentum space,

00:18:11.850 --> 00:18:13.870
but it does make sense
in position space--

00:18:13.870 --> 00:18:16.340
we can even do a
first approximation

00:18:16.340 --> 00:18:19.470
where we completely
neglect those fluctuations.

00:18:19.470 --> 00:18:22.190
And then what we have
is when we simply

00:18:22.190 --> 00:18:28.600
insert a [? Z ?] number
into this Hamiltonian.

00:18:28.600 --> 00:18:33.310
We have then an equation
for this number,

00:18:33.310 --> 00:18:34.870
for this function psi.

00:18:34.870 --> 00:18:37.600
And this is the nonlinear
Schrodinger equation,

00:18:37.600 --> 00:18:40.730
or it's also called
Gross-Pitaevskii equation,

00:18:40.730 --> 00:18:44.990
which is now the analogy
to Schrodinger's equation,

00:18:44.990 --> 00:18:48.000
but now for the macroscopic
wave function which

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:51.250
is occupied by many,
many particles.

00:18:51.250 --> 00:18:53.470
And in addition to
the kinetic energy

00:18:53.470 --> 00:18:57.760
and the trapping potential
in the external potential,

00:18:57.760 --> 00:19:01.740
it has a term which is
proportional to the density.

00:19:01.740 --> 00:19:05.620
And this is just
mean field repulsion

00:19:05.620 --> 00:19:11.060
which one atom feels
exerted by the other atoms.

00:19:11.060 --> 00:19:15.080
I should say--
just to connect it

00:19:15.080 --> 00:19:18.250
to what I've said earlier
about the quantum depletion--

00:19:18.250 --> 00:19:22.740
that you can regard the
function psi as the best

00:19:22.740 --> 00:19:26.340
approximation to an ideal
Bose-Einstein condensate.

00:19:26.340 --> 00:19:28.470
So if you want to write
your many-body wave

00:19:28.470 --> 00:19:32.300
function as a function
psi to the power N,

00:19:32.300 --> 00:19:35.350
all particles are in
the same quantum state,

00:19:35.350 --> 00:19:38.720
then a variational
calculation would

00:19:38.720 --> 00:19:43.960
say that this function psi
should obey this equation.

00:19:43.960 --> 00:19:45.560
If you want to read
up what I've said,

00:19:45.560 --> 00:19:49.150
I've posted a recent paper,
which I found very pedagogical,

00:19:49.150 --> 00:19:53.510
where they derive the
Gross-Pitaevskii equation

00:19:53.510 --> 00:19:56.570
without even using an
operator psi dagger,

00:19:56.570 --> 00:19:58.940
without using any
second quantization.

00:19:58.940 --> 00:20:02.810
They just say we have an
Hamiltonian for an interaction

00:20:02.810 --> 00:20:08.780
system, and we try to write
the complicated, many-body wave

00:20:08.780 --> 00:20:13.810
function as a wave
function to the power N.

00:20:13.810 --> 00:20:17.250
And then you put this
ansatz into your Hamiltonian

00:20:17.250 --> 00:20:21.330
and do a variation optimization
which single-particle wave

00:20:21.330 --> 00:20:25.020
function psi, if
taken to the power N,

00:20:25.020 --> 00:20:28.220
minimizes the total
energy of N particles,

00:20:28.220 --> 00:20:29.970
including interactions.

00:20:29.970 --> 00:20:33.500
And the answer is this equation.

00:20:33.500 --> 00:20:35.160
So there are many
ways this equation

00:20:35.160 --> 00:20:37.200
is sort of very natural.

00:20:40.120 --> 00:20:45.510
Now you all know about
single-particle physics--

00:20:45.510 --> 00:20:47.640
kinetic energy in an
external potential.

00:20:47.640 --> 00:20:51.310
Let's now learn what this
density-dependent term does.

00:20:51.310 --> 00:20:53.220
Well, it's pretty clear.

00:20:53.220 --> 00:20:56.650
There is a price to
be paid for density.

00:20:56.650 --> 00:21:00.330
And while the total
integrated density, of course,

00:21:00.330 --> 00:21:02.600
is given by the total
number of particles.

00:21:02.600 --> 00:21:05.460
That means if you lower
the density somewhere,

00:21:05.460 --> 00:21:07.890
you have to increase
the density.

00:21:07.890 --> 00:21:11.350
But because this is
a non-linear term,

00:21:11.350 --> 00:21:14.090
if you have an average
density and you lower it

00:21:14.090 --> 00:21:18.340
here and increase it here, you
have actually more repulsive

00:21:18.340 --> 00:21:21.170
energy than if the
density is flat.

00:21:21.170 --> 00:21:23.780
So this term has only one goal.

00:21:23.780 --> 00:21:27.660
It wants to flatten
out densities.

00:21:27.660 --> 00:21:31.530
So therefore if we
have a box potential

00:21:31.530 --> 00:21:33.240
and you know the
ground state in a box

00:21:33.240 --> 00:21:37.180
is just half a period
of a sine function.

00:21:39.730 --> 00:21:41.964
This is a non-interacting
condensate.

00:21:41.964 --> 00:21:43.380
This would be the
macroscopic wave

00:21:43.380 --> 00:21:44.810
function in a box potential.

00:21:44.810 --> 00:21:47.360
But if you now put in
strong interactions,

00:21:47.360 --> 00:21:51.290
the strong interaction's going
to flatten out the potential.

00:21:51.290 --> 00:21:54.190
They flatten out the
potential, and only at the very

00:21:54.190 --> 00:21:56.570
last moment-- all
right, now it's

00:21:56.570 --> 00:22:00.550
time to go down because we have
to meet our boundary condition.

00:22:00.550 --> 00:22:04.520
And the length scale where
you eventually go down-- it

00:22:04.520 --> 00:22:07.100
has a famous name,
the healing length--

00:22:07.100 --> 00:22:10.720
is the length scale
where the kinetic energy

00:22:10.720 --> 00:22:13.080
due to the curvature
of the wave function

00:22:13.080 --> 00:22:17.330
is now comparable to
the interaction energy.

00:22:17.330 --> 00:22:19.560
If the system would
curve down earlier,

00:22:19.560 --> 00:22:23.130
it would cause too
much repulsive energy,

00:22:23.130 --> 00:22:25.150
because the density
is not kept flat.

00:22:25.150 --> 00:22:28.280
If it would curve down too
late, the enormous curvature

00:22:28.280 --> 00:22:30.020
would mean a lot
of kinetic energy.

00:22:30.020 --> 00:22:31.520
And this is just
the best compromise

00:22:31.520 --> 00:22:33.570
between those two criteria.

00:22:33.570 --> 00:22:36.150
So that's how you derive
the healing length.

00:22:36.150 --> 00:22:38.580
The healing length is
now the length scale

00:22:38.580 --> 00:22:45.010
over which the system is willing
to meet boundary conditions,

00:22:45.010 --> 00:22:49.080
and not stay flat,
as flat as possible.

00:22:49.080 --> 00:22:49.845
Yes.

00:22:49.845 --> 00:22:51.594
AUDIENCE: Just curious--
in that equation,

00:22:51.594 --> 00:22:57.180
the atom has the mass
of each individual--

00:22:57.180 --> 00:22:59.476
PROFESSOR: The mass is
the mass of a single atom.

00:22:59.476 --> 00:23:02.260
AUDIENCE: Single atom,
it's not-- sorry,

00:23:02.260 --> 00:23:03.260
I wasn't here last time.

00:23:03.260 --> 00:23:06.580
But the quasiparticles are
the same mass [INAUDIBLE].

00:23:06.580 --> 00:23:08.880
PROFESSOR: In a Bose-Einstein
condensate they are.

00:23:08.880 --> 00:23:11.070
We haven't changed the mass.

00:23:11.070 --> 00:23:13.350
But we're not talking
actually about quasiparticle.

00:23:13.350 --> 00:23:18.810
We're actually really talking
about here qualitative features

00:23:18.810 --> 00:23:22.020
of the solution of the
Gross-Pitaevskii equation.

00:23:22.020 --> 00:23:23.670
And the Gross-Pitaevskii
equation

00:23:23.670 --> 00:23:27.990
is sort of a single particle
equation for particles of mass,

00:23:27.990 --> 00:23:32.650
of the original bare mass
M. It's a macroscopic wave

00:23:32.650 --> 00:23:35.520
function, but I sometimes say
it describes the wave function

00:23:35.520 --> 00:23:38.520
of a single particle where
all the other particles are

00:23:38.520 --> 00:23:40.610
included at the
mean field level.

00:23:40.610 --> 00:23:43.120
So therefore, it is really
this, the atomic mass,

00:23:43.120 --> 00:23:46.460
and not any form of
collective mass here.

00:23:46.460 --> 00:23:49.640
Well, if you would now
ask how do interactions

00:23:49.640 --> 00:23:56.510
transform the first excited
state in the box potential?

00:23:56.510 --> 00:24:00.410
Well, then it's again flat
this as much as possible.

00:24:00.410 --> 00:24:03.760
But then if you want to
maintain the parity of the wave

00:24:03.760 --> 00:24:06.430
function, then it's
only close to the zero

00:24:06.430 --> 00:24:10.570
crossing within a healing length
that the system says OK, now I

00:24:10.570 --> 00:24:12.360
change sign.

00:24:12.360 --> 00:24:18.080
So that's sort of what is inside
the Gross-Pitaevskii equation.

00:24:18.080 --> 00:24:23.440
Now once we realize that, we
can take it to the next level

00:24:23.440 --> 00:24:26.781
and say, well, if you
neglect-- let's say

00:24:26.781 --> 00:24:28.280
we're interested
in the ground state

00:24:28.280 --> 00:24:30.530
and we neglect this
boundary region where

00:24:30.530 --> 00:24:33.130
the kinetic energy
becomes important-- maybe

00:24:33.130 --> 00:24:35.920
we can simplify the
Gross-Pitaevskii equation

00:24:35.920 --> 00:24:38.846
by neglecting the
kinetic energy.

00:24:38.846 --> 00:24:43.580
If potential energy dominates
by far, we can neglect that.

00:24:43.580 --> 00:24:45.670
And then we should
get a good description

00:24:45.670 --> 00:24:49.510
which will not be valid in
the wings of the wave function

00:24:49.510 --> 00:24:53.210
but in most of space.

00:24:53.210 --> 00:24:54.941
But now if you look
at this equation,

00:24:54.941 --> 00:24:56.565
it's no longer a
differential equation.

00:24:56.565 --> 00:24:58.120
It has no derivatives.

00:24:58.120 --> 00:25:01.530
It's just something
which applies

00:25:01.530 --> 00:25:04.500
to the wave function psi itself.

00:25:04.500 --> 00:25:09.140
And we can simply solve that.

00:25:09.140 --> 00:25:11.580
The solution of that
is that psi squared--

00:25:11.580 --> 00:25:15.370
the density-- is
nothing else than there

00:25:15.370 --> 00:25:20.000
is a constant minus the
inverted trapping potential.

00:25:20.000 --> 00:25:24.550
So therefore in this
Thomas-Fermi approximation

00:25:24.550 --> 00:25:27.390
where we neglect the
kinetic energy completely,

00:25:27.390 --> 00:25:32.010
you just take your trapping
potential, turn it upside down,

00:25:32.010 --> 00:25:34.790
and then you fill
it up with density

00:25:34.790 --> 00:25:37.500
until you have accommodated
the number of atoms

00:25:37.500 --> 00:25:38.890
you want to accommodate.

00:25:38.890 --> 00:25:41.084
And this is, of
course-- the constraint

00:25:41.084 --> 00:25:43.250
in the number of atoms is
determined by the chemical

00:25:43.250 --> 00:25:44.490
potential.

00:25:44.490 --> 00:25:48.100
Or if you have a more
complicated W-shaped potential,

00:25:48.100 --> 00:25:49.420
the same construction.

00:25:49.420 --> 00:25:54.070
Flip it over, fill it up,
gives you the condensate wave

00:25:54.070 --> 00:25:56.180
function, the
density distribution

00:25:56.180 --> 00:26:00.150
of the condensate
in this potential.

00:26:00.150 --> 00:26:02.940
I don't want to belabor
it, but coming back

00:26:02.940 --> 00:26:05.680
to the question of
the small parameter,

00:26:05.680 --> 00:26:08.240
if you look at
those equations, you

00:26:08.240 --> 00:26:13.290
can identify a parameter-- this
is now the small parameter,

00:26:13.290 --> 00:26:16.060
or the parameter
in the system which

00:26:16.060 --> 00:26:19.030
is the important
dimensionless parameter.

00:26:19.030 --> 00:26:20.950
It depends on the
number of atoms,

00:26:20.950 --> 00:26:24.470
and it depends now on the ratio
of the scattering length--

00:26:24.470 --> 00:26:26.590
which characterizes
the interaction--

00:26:26.590 --> 00:26:29.860
and the harmonic
oscillator length.

00:26:29.860 --> 00:26:31.520
You can say the
harmonic oscillator

00:26:31.520 --> 00:26:36.720
length is the ideal wave
function harmonic oscillator.

00:26:36.720 --> 00:26:39.790
So this parametrizes the
importance of kinetic energy,

00:26:39.790 --> 00:26:42.180
whereas the scattering
length parametrizes

00:26:42.180 --> 00:26:44.160
the importance of interactions.

00:26:44.160 --> 00:26:48.930
And all those solutions
can be nicely written

00:26:48.930 --> 00:26:53.750
as what you would
have in an ideal gas,

00:26:53.750 --> 00:26:59.600
and then this parameter X. So
in typical experiments, N a,

00:26:59.600 --> 00:27:00.871
N is a million.

00:27:00.871 --> 00:27:03.370
The scattering length is smaller
than the oscillator length,

00:27:03.370 --> 00:27:08.440
but N is a million, and this
parameter X is usually large.

00:27:08.440 --> 00:27:11.370
So therefore-- and I'm
simply just talking

00:27:11.370 --> 00:27:14.840
about this solution-- we have
the situation that the chemical

00:27:14.840 --> 00:27:17.720
potential is larger
by a power of X

00:27:17.720 --> 00:27:22.400
than the ideal gas solution,
which would just be the ground

00:27:22.400 --> 00:27:25.910
state with its zero point energy
in the harmonic oscillator

00:27:25.910 --> 00:27:31.620
potential, or the width-- the
size-- of the wave function

00:27:31.620 --> 00:27:35.690
is larger than the ground state
of the harmonic oscillator,

00:27:35.690 --> 00:27:40.100
but only with an exponent,
which is one-fifth.

00:27:40.100 --> 00:27:42.290
Well, we can see that.

00:27:42.290 --> 00:27:45.580
These are now, again,
somewhat improved pictures

00:27:45.580 --> 00:27:47.670
of condensates inside the trap.

00:27:47.670 --> 00:27:49.860
For the expert, the
previous picture

00:27:49.860 --> 00:27:51.160
was dark-ground imaging.

00:27:51.160 --> 00:27:53.960
This is now
phase-contrast imaging.

00:27:53.960 --> 00:27:56.510
And if you take a
profile, we clearly

00:27:56.510 --> 00:28:02.370
see the condensate wave function
and we see the thermal wings.

00:28:02.370 --> 00:28:07.450
When we look at the size of
the condensate wave function,

00:28:07.450 --> 00:28:11.594
you realize what I just meant--
that the ground-state wave

00:28:11.594 --> 00:28:13.260
function, the harmonic
oscillator length

00:28:13.260 --> 00:28:15.980
is 7 micron in the
axial direction,

00:28:15.980 --> 00:28:18.650
but here you have 300 micron.

00:28:18.650 --> 00:28:23.850
So this condensate is completely
dominated by interactions.

00:28:23.850 --> 00:28:30.720
And it fulfils very nice, and
pretty much the whole shape,

00:28:30.720 --> 00:28:33.150
except maybe some
details in the wings,

00:28:33.150 --> 00:28:40.030
are quantitatively described
by the simple approximation

00:28:40.030 --> 00:28:42.270
I have explained to you.

00:28:42.270 --> 00:28:44.020
So just a little
bit show and tell.

00:28:44.020 --> 00:28:47.660
We have this
Gross-Pitaevskii equation.

00:28:47.660 --> 00:28:50.680
The Gross-Pitaevskii equation
has, as Schrodinger's equation,

00:28:50.680 --> 00:28:53.320
a time independent form
to get the ground state.

00:28:53.320 --> 00:28:56.240
It has also a time
dependent form.

00:28:56.240 --> 00:28:58.840
You simply replace the
energy by the derivative

00:28:58.840 --> 00:28:59.750
of the wave function.

00:28:59.750 --> 00:29:01.580
This is the time-dependent form.

00:29:01.580 --> 00:29:06.170
Everything is very simple, and
you can do many-body physics,

00:29:06.170 --> 00:29:07.991
but on your computer,
you pretty much look

00:29:07.991 --> 00:29:09.365
for single-particle
wave function

00:29:09.365 --> 00:29:11.690
and take them to the power N.

00:29:11.690 --> 00:29:14.280
So some areas where the
Gross-Pitaevskii equation

00:29:14.280 --> 00:29:17.820
has quantitatively
explained experiments-- one

00:29:17.820 --> 00:29:21.590
is the expansion of a
Bose-Einstein condensate.

00:29:21.590 --> 00:29:23.540
It's this famous
situation when you

00:29:23.540 --> 00:29:26.570
have an elongated condensate
and let it expand.

00:29:26.570 --> 00:29:31.760
It expands faster in
the radial direction.

00:29:31.760 --> 00:29:33.970
One simple argument
is the pressure

00:29:33.970 --> 00:29:37.900
of the mean field is larger and
leads to faster acceleration.

00:29:37.900 --> 00:29:40.150
So therefore, if you have
a cigar-shaped condensate

00:29:40.150 --> 00:29:45.230
and release it, it
turns into a disk.

00:29:45.230 --> 00:29:48.790
It inverts the aspect ratio,
going from a cigar shape

00:29:48.790 --> 00:29:50.030
to a disk shape.

00:29:50.030 --> 00:29:53.270
And that has been beautifully
and quantitatively described

00:29:53.270 --> 00:29:55.960
by the Gross-Pitaevskii
equation.

00:29:55.960 --> 00:29:58.550
Here we have measured
the interaction energy

00:29:58.550 --> 00:30:00.740
as a number of condensed atoms.

00:30:00.740 --> 00:30:05.370
And I mentioned to you that
this X parameter comes often

00:30:05.370 --> 00:30:07.750
with power 1/5 and 2/5.

00:30:07.750 --> 00:30:10.154
And this here is a
fit to the power 2/5,

00:30:10.154 --> 00:30:11.570
beautifully
confirming the theory.

00:30:17.390 --> 00:30:19.400
So the Gross-Pitaevskii
equation was

00:30:19.400 --> 00:30:26.680
invented in 1962, about 50 years
ago by Gross and Pitaevskii

00:30:26.680 --> 00:30:29.260
to describe vortices.

00:30:29.260 --> 00:30:34.450
Actually, Lev Pitaevskii
is still alive,

00:30:34.450 --> 00:30:38.200
going strong, and
publishing papers.

00:30:38.200 --> 00:30:42.210
One of his latest predictions
was solitons in Fermi gases,

00:30:42.210 --> 00:30:46.000
and I know in Professor
Zwierlein's group,

00:30:46.000 --> 00:30:49.760
one of his lab just looked
at the same physics,

00:30:49.760 --> 00:30:52.440
and compared to the
theory of Lev Pitaevskii.

00:30:52.440 --> 00:30:55.610
And this year we
are celebrating--

00:30:55.610 --> 00:30:58.200
I forgot, the 85th or
90th birthday of him.

00:30:58.200 --> 00:31:00.190
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:31:00.190 --> 00:31:00.866
PROFESSOR: 90?

00:31:00.866 --> 00:31:01.990
AUDIENCE: There's a poster.

00:31:01.990 --> 00:31:04.180
PROFESSOR: I know there's
a poster next to my door,

00:31:04.180 --> 00:31:06.600
but I forgot which anniversary.

00:31:06.600 --> 00:31:10.430
So I mean, he's an legend.

00:31:10.430 --> 00:31:12.110
But he's still walking.

00:31:12.110 --> 00:31:13.750
He's still doing science.

00:31:13.750 --> 00:31:18.840
So if you meet him, you go
back to 50 years in history.

00:31:18.840 --> 00:31:21.700
Anyway, it is this
Lev Pitaevskii,

00:31:21.700 --> 00:31:27.410
and he invented his equations
to describe vortices.

00:31:27.410 --> 00:31:32.640
So anyway so we have this
nonlinear Schrodinger equation.

00:31:32.640 --> 00:31:34.660
Let me just show you
what vortices are

00:31:34.660 --> 00:31:37.340
and how they are formed.

00:31:37.340 --> 00:31:42.710
Vortices come-- if you solve
the Gross-Pitaevskii equation--

00:31:42.710 --> 00:31:45.090
if you ever any quantum
fluid or quantum gas,

00:31:45.090 --> 00:31:49.410
and you add angular momentum,
the angular momentum cannot

00:31:49.410 --> 00:31:51.820
lead to rigid body rotation.

00:31:51.820 --> 00:31:55.500
This would violate the fact
that the velocity field has

00:31:55.500 --> 00:31:58.640
to be irrotational to make
sure that the phase of the wave

00:31:58.640 --> 00:32:01.320
function is well defined.

00:32:01.320 --> 00:32:06.620
So if you rotate the system,
it can absorb angular momentum

00:32:06.620 --> 00:32:09.050
only by forming vortices.

00:32:09.050 --> 00:32:13.390
And vortices are singular points
of the wave function-- singular

00:32:13.390 --> 00:32:16.770
points where the density is 0.

00:32:16.770 --> 00:32:21.100
In other words-- I don't have
time to be exhaustive here--

00:32:21.100 --> 00:32:23.090
but when something
rotates, there

00:32:23.090 --> 00:32:26.397
is a dynamic phase you
can say, because there

00:32:26.397 --> 00:32:28.230
are matter waves
going in circles.

00:32:28.230 --> 00:32:30.320
And the integral
of the phase has

00:32:30.320 --> 00:32:33.525
to be an integer number
of 2 pi, otherwise

00:32:33.525 --> 00:32:35.650
you would not have a
well-defined phase of the wave

00:32:35.650 --> 00:32:36.790
function.

00:32:36.790 --> 00:32:39.920
And if you now say you make
a circle, which is 2 pi.

00:32:39.920 --> 00:32:42.170
You make the circle
smaller, smaller, smaller.

00:32:42.170 --> 00:32:44.410
In the middle of the
circle, you go around.

00:32:44.410 --> 00:32:46.620
The wave function
changes by 2 pi,

00:32:46.620 --> 00:32:49.200
but what should the wave
function do on one point?

00:32:49.200 --> 00:32:52.990
Which number between 0 and 2 pi
should the wave function peak?

00:32:52.990 --> 00:32:55.010
Well, the wave function
says I can't peak.

00:32:55.010 --> 00:32:56.500
I just go to 0.

00:32:56.500 --> 00:32:59.360
And a 0 value has no
phase and I'm fine.

00:32:59.360 --> 00:33:01.640
That's exactly what the
wave function tells you.

00:33:01.640 --> 00:33:04.290
So therefore if you want
to describe vortices,

00:33:04.290 --> 00:33:08.000
you want to now describe the
Gross-Pitaevskii equation,

00:33:08.000 --> 00:33:11.140
but with the boundary condition
that the wave function

00:33:11.140 --> 00:33:12.520
goes to 0.

00:33:12.520 --> 00:33:14.530
And if you want to
describe one vortex,

00:33:14.530 --> 00:33:20.130
you want the wave function to
go 0 in the center of the cloud.

00:33:20.130 --> 00:33:23.010
And so you make a
corresponding Ansatz.

00:33:23.010 --> 00:33:26.310
You allow the phase to
wrap around by 2 pi,

00:33:26.310 --> 00:33:28.530
when the angle phi is varied.

00:33:28.530 --> 00:33:32.210
And then when you solve
it, you have, of course,

00:33:32.210 --> 00:33:37.280
put in that there should be a
0 of the density at the center.

00:33:37.280 --> 00:33:41.230
And it's now nice for me to--
there's an important review

00:33:41.230 --> 00:33:43.120
paper which describes
all that and more--

00:33:43.120 --> 00:33:45.610
but it's nice to
show you now the two

00:33:45.610 --> 00:33:49.680
extreme cases of the ideal
condensate without interaction,

00:33:49.680 --> 00:33:52.190
and the strong
interacting condensate.

00:33:52.190 --> 00:33:57.090
The ideal condensate-- well, we
are in the first excited state

00:33:57.090 --> 00:33:59.480
of the harmonic
oscillator potential.

00:33:59.480 --> 00:34:01.580
And this is the dashed line.

00:34:01.580 --> 00:34:06.120
And of course, the size
of the whole, the 0,

00:34:06.120 --> 00:34:09.090
is pretty much on the order
of the oscillator length,

00:34:09.090 --> 00:34:10.960
because there is no
other length scale

00:34:10.960 --> 00:34:13.440
in the ideal
harmonic oscillator.

00:34:13.440 --> 00:34:15.949
But if you have the
interacting system,

00:34:15.949 --> 00:34:18.360
remember what
interactions are doing.

00:34:18.360 --> 00:34:21.630
They want to keep the density
as constant as possible.

00:34:21.630 --> 00:34:23.300
Well, we are not
in a box potential.

00:34:23.300 --> 00:34:26.050
We're in an inverted
parabola potential.

00:34:26.050 --> 00:34:28.489
And remember, our
Thomas-Fermi solution,

00:34:28.489 --> 00:34:32.650
which neglects kinetic energy,
is the inverted parabola

00:34:32.650 --> 00:34:33.780
up to here.

00:34:33.780 --> 00:34:36.285
And then the tail is
when we can no longer

00:34:36.285 --> 00:34:38.429
neglect the kinetic energy.

00:34:38.429 --> 00:34:41.720
But if we now say, OK, fine,
but now in addition, we

00:34:41.720 --> 00:34:43.679
want a vortex in
the center, the wave

00:34:43.679 --> 00:34:45.650
function out there says no.

00:34:45.650 --> 00:34:48.040
We do what minimizes
kinetic energy,

00:34:48.040 --> 00:34:51.850
and what minimizes
repulsive energy.

00:34:51.850 --> 00:34:54.520
We follow the inverted
parabola, and only

00:34:54.520 --> 00:34:59.970
at the very last moment-- on
the scale of the healing length,

00:34:59.970 --> 00:35:02.700
the system meets the
required boundary condition

00:35:02.700 --> 00:35:05.400
that the density goes to 0.

00:35:05.400 --> 00:35:07.510
Anyway, with this
qualitative understanding,

00:35:07.510 --> 00:35:08.930
you can get a lot out of those.

00:35:08.930 --> 00:35:11.300
You can immediately
understand the salient feature

00:35:11.300 --> 00:35:12.100
of the solution.

00:35:15.274 --> 00:35:16.242
Question?

00:35:16.242 --> 00:35:18.178
AUDIENCE: I know we're
not talking details,

00:35:18.178 --> 00:35:20.350
but is there a simple,
maybe clear reason why

00:35:20.350 --> 00:35:22.802
when you spin a
Bose-Einstein condensate

00:35:22.802 --> 00:35:25.085
you get many vortices, but
when you spin your coffee

00:35:25.085 --> 00:35:28.285
in your cup, you
just get one big one?

00:35:28.285 --> 00:35:28.910
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:35:33.430 --> 00:35:39.720
So the question is, if I have
a wrap-around of 4 pi in phase,

00:35:39.720 --> 00:35:48.575
whether the system should have
a doubly charged vortex, or two

00:35:48.575 --> 00:35:50.740
singly charged vortices?

00:35:50.740 --> 00:35:53.660
What is the
difference in energy?

00:35:53.660 --> 00:35:58.760
Well, what happens is doubly
charged vortices are unstable.

00:35:58.760 --> 00:36:00.842
My group, at some point,
were the first to create

00:36:00.842 --> 00:36:02.300
doubly charged
vortices, but we saw

00:36:02.300 --> 00:36:04.815
that they immediately decayed.

00:36:04.815 --> 00:36:05.690
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:36:05.690 --> 00:36:06.370
PROFESSOR: Pardon?

00:36:06.370 --> 00:36:07.286
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:36:10.310 --> 00:36:12.060
PROFESSOR: Initially,
we couldn't observe.

00:36:12.060 --> 00:36:14.810
We just saw that
it was unstable.

00:36:14.810 --> 00:36:16.560
But it's a decay
into two vortices.

00:36:16.560 --> 00:36:18.220
But it's easy to understand.

00:36:18.220 --> 00:36:21.280
If you put two vortices
on top of each other,

00:36:21.280 --> 00:36:25.110
what is the energy of the
system compared to one vortex?

00:36:25.110 --> 00:36:29.550
Well, the energy of a vortex is
the rotational field around it,

00:36:29.550 --> 00:36:32.420
and if you superimpose
two vortices,

00:36:32.420 --> 00:36:35.450
the velocity around the
doubly charged vortices

00:36:35.450 --> 00:36:38.500
is twice the velocity
of one vortex.

00:36:38.500 --> 00:36:42.300
And therefore, the kinetic
energy is four times.

00:36:42.300 --> 00:36:44.210
If you have two
vortices which are

00:36:44.210 --> 00:36:47.620
far separated that it has
its own velocity field.

00:36:47.620 --> 00:36:49.580
It has its own
velocity field here.

00:36:49.580 --> 00:36:51.970
And when the two velocity
fields come together,

00:36:51.970 --> 00:36:55.150
the velocity is
already so low that you

00:36:55.150 --> 00:36:58.400
don't have to consider that,
then those two vortices have

00:36:58.400 --> 00:37:02.550
an energy which is two times
the energy of a single vortex.

00:37:02.550 --> 00:37:04.980
So therefore, when
the two vortices,

00:37:04.980 --> 00:37:08.260
they start out with four times
the energy of a single vortex,

00:37:08.260 --> 00:37:11.170
and when they dissociate
and repel each other,

00:37:11.170 --> 00:37:13.850
they have shed half
of their energy.

00:37:13.850 --> 00:37:16.230
So this argument
tells you immediately

00:37:16.230 --> 00:37:19.850
that vortices are
in effect repulsive.

00:37:19.850 --> 00:37:23.530
And therefore, any
multiple-charged vortex

00:37:23.530 --> 00:37:27.170
will spontaneously decay.

00:37:27.170 --> 00:37:30.110
It's also this net
repulsion between vortices

00:37:30.110 --> 00:37:33.800
which makes the vortices
arrange in a regular lattice.

00:37:33.800 --> 00:37:36.090
The regular lattice
which you saw before

00:37:36.090 --> 00:37:39.120
is Nature's answer to
how can we minimize

00:37:39.120 --> 00:37:41.270
the energy of all
those vortices?

00:37:41.270 --> 00:37:44.990
And the idea is let's keep the
average distance between them

00:37:44.990 --> 00:37:49.230
as large as possible, and the
answer is a hexagonal lattice.

00:37:49.230 --> 00:37:51.870
Yeah.

00:37:51.870 --> 00:37:55.060
AUDIENCE: So a few
slides back, when

00:37:55.060 --> 00:38:01.120
you write the G-P equation, when
you plotted sort of for the box

00:38:01.120 --> 00:38:04.920
potential, the ground state
and the excited state comparing

00:38:04.920 --> 00:38:08.510
the G-P equation to the typical
single-particle [INAUDIBLE].

00:38:08.510 --> 00:38:11.472
And so I guess I'm a
little bit confused

00:38:11.472 --> 00:38:15.040
about how excitations manifest
themselves in the system.

00:38:15.040 --> 00:38:18.730
Because in some sense, if you
were to solve the G-P equation,

00:38:18.730 --> 00:38:25.180
would you arrive at a
spectrum of solutions?

00:38:25.180 --> 00:38:28.150
Then I guess I'd be confused
at whether excitations manifest

00:38:28.150 --> 00:38:30.490
themselves into that
spectrum of solutions,

00:38:30.490 --> 00:38:35.990
or rather than they become
excitations, sort of deviations

00:38:35.990 --> 00:38:39.706
from the mean field as
including the [INAUDIBLE].

00:38:39.706 --> 00:38:41.580
PROFESSOR: You are now
asking about something

00:38:41.580 --> 00:38:42.288
more complicated.

00:38:42.288 --> 00:38:43.740
You're asking what
are the excited

00:38:43.740 --> 00:38:45.690
states of the many-body system?

00:38:45.690 --> 00:38:48.900
And actually, we have
already found one answer.

00:38:48.900 --> 00:38:53.200
And this is if you want
these small excitations,

00:38:53.200 --> 00:38:56.020
it's one particle
becomes a phonon,

00:38:56.020 --> 00:38:58.990
or one particle becomes
a quasiparticle.

00:38:58.990 --> 00:39:01.300
What we are talking
about here is

00:39:01.300 --> 00:39:04.840
what happens if the
whole macroscopic wave

00:39:04.840 --> 00:39:07.020
function is in an excited state.

00:39:07.020 --> 00:39:09.600
So we are asking here in
the box potential what

00:39:09.600 --> 00:39:15.030
happens if you force all N atoms
to have one node in the wave

00:39:15.030 --> 00:39:15.620
function.

00:39:15.620 --> 00:39:17.590
And this is what I'm
talking about here.

00:39:17.590 --> 00:39:20.400
So the excitation
energy of this state

00:39:20.400 --> 00:39:24.300
here is much, much higher
than of single quasiparticle

00:39:24.300 --> 00:39:26.010
excitations.

00:39:26.010 --> 00:39:29.580
I'm not sure if I'm addressing
your question here, but--

00:39:29.580 --> 00:39:32.585
AUDIENCE: So with
single quasiparticle

00:39:32.585 --> 00:39:34.209
excitations, are
those essentially sort

00:39:34.209 --> 00:39:35.682
of deviations from
the mean field?

00:39:40.570 --> 00:39:43.280
PROFESSOR: No, they
are-- you really

00:39:43.280 --> 00:39:52.390
look for many-body physics--
main field deviations--

00:39:52.390 --> 00:39:53.550
probably.

00:39:53.550 --> 00:40:00.500
I mean, what you do
is in that sense, yes.

00:40:00.500 --> 00:40:04.070
You're allowing in this
Ansatz that psi operator

00:40:04.070 --> 00:40:07.040
is psi average
plus fluctuations.

00:40:07.040 --> 00:40:09.710
You now look for
fluctuations, and you're

00:40:09.710 --> 00:40:12.200
looking for the
energy eigenspectrum

00:40:12.200 --> 00:40:14.090
of those fluctuations.

00:40:14.090 --> 00:40:16.840
And the answer are
quasiparticles.

00:40:16.840 --> 00:40:21.000
So it is, actually,
the Bogoliubov solution

00:40:21.000 --> 00:40:26.090
for the spectrum of
the fluctuations.

00:40:26.090 --> 00:40:30.440
And the answer is the dispersion
relation I presented to you.

00:40:30.440 --> 00:40:33.740
Whereas here we
are asking what are

00:40:33.740 --> 00:40:36.600
excited states of the
macroscopic wave function?

00:40:36.600 --> 00:40:38.330
It's a very, very
different question

00:40:38.330 --> 00:40:40.660
which we've addressed here.

00:40:40.660 --> 00:40:41.510
Yes.

00:40:41.510 --> 00:40:43.259
AUDIENCE: So when you
stir the condensate,

00:40:43.259 --> 00:40:48.310
do you view it as-- do you
stir, sort of, at the trap

00:40:48.310 --> 00:40:51.312
frequency, so I do sort
of N single excitations?

00:40:51.312 --> 00:40:55.866
Or do you stir at N
times the trap frequency,

00:40:55.866 --> 00:40:59.608
so you get one sort of
N particle excitation?

00:40:59.608 --> 00:41:01.590
PROFESSOR: Well, the
experimental answer

00:41:01.590 --> 00:41:04.140
is you want to stir at the
quadrupole frequency, which

00:41:04.140 --> 00:41:07.100
is square root 2 times
the trap frequency.

00:41:07.100 --> 00:41:10.080
Then you create
quadrupolar excitations.

00:41:10.080 --> 00:41:14.660
The quadrupolar excitation can
be regarded as a standing sound

00:41:14.660 --> 00:41:17.990
wave, but you create
a macroscopic number

00:41:17.990 --> 00:41:19.730
of those excitations.

00:41:19.730 --> 00:41:22.450
So you make, actually, the
whole condensate wave function

00:41:22.450 --> 00:41:25.680
oscillate in a
quadrupolar pattern,

00:41:25.680 --> 00:41:28.390
but it's a rotating
quadrupole, and that

00:41:28.390 --> 00:41:33.620
eventually then rearranges
itself and leads to vortices.

00:41:33.620 --> 00:41:40.070
So I think the correct answer
is the most efficient way

00:41:40.070 --> 00:41:45.350
to create vortices would be to
excite quasiparticles, but then

00:41:45.350 --> 00:41:49.150
create so many-- and this may
relate to Matt's question--

00:41:49.150 --> 00:41:52.490
create so many quasiparticles
that you have really

00:41:52.490 --> 00:41:55.570
a time-dependent and oscillating
macroscopic wave function.

00:42:00.300 --> 00:42:02.990
So eventually, you have
a coherent excitation

00:42:02.990 --> 00:42:04.200
of quasiparticles.

00:42:04.200 --> 00:42:06.780
And that eventually means
the condensate moves

00:42:06.780 --> 00:42:10.310
in a quadrupolar pattern, but
it's a quadrupolar pattern

00:42:10.310 --> 00:42:12.290
with rotation, and
that eventually

00:42:12.290 --> 00:42:15.940
turns into many vortices.

00:42:15.940 --> 00:42:19.500
But that's really a very rich
question which you're asking,

00:42:19.500 --> 00:42:24.210
which has been studied-- a lot
of different aspects of that

00:42:24.210 --> 00:42:24.960
have been studied.

00:42:30.220 --> 00:42:35.760
OK, so we've talked about
Bose-Einstein condensates

00:42:35.760 --> 00:42:39.350
in a homogeneous system, just
sort of to lay the groundwork.

00:42:39.350 --> 00:42:41.570
We've talked about
Bose-Einstein condensates

00:42:41.570 --> 00:42:44.150
in traps in
inhomogeneous system.

