Now we want to talk about
Bose-Einstein condensates

00:42:47.070 --> 00:42:48.850
in optical lattices.

00:42:48.850 --> 00:42:52.050
Well, there are two reasons
why we want to do that.

00:42:52.050 --> 00:42:56.390
One is we want to use the
Bose-Einstein condensate

00:42:56.390 --> 00:43:00.490
to obtain deeper insight into
the properties of matter.

00:43:00.490 --> 00:43:05.640
And a lot of forms of matter
appear in periodic lattices.

00:43:05.640 --> 00:43:07.990
So if you put a
Bose-Einstein condensate

00:43:07.990 --> 00:43:11.580
into a periodic
potential, we can at least

00:43:11.580 --> 00:43:14.700
understand some
of the properties

00:43:14.700 --> 00:43:17.870
of crystalline
matter, or electrons

00:43:17.870 --> 00:43:22.200
which are block waves
in a periodic potential.

00:43:22.200 --> 00:43:24.470
So this is one reason why.

00:43:24.470 --> 00:43:27.630
The other reason why we want
to go to optical lattices

00:43:27.630 --> 00:43:31.530
is the following-- ideal
Bose-Einstein condensates

00:43:31.530 --> 00:43:33.580
are trivial.

00:43:33.580 --> 00:43:39.020
Weakly interacting Bose-Einstein
condensates are entertaining,

00:43:39.020 --> 00:43:41.570
and you can write a lot of
papers, have a lot of fun

00:43:41.570 --> 00:43:45.800
with it, develop your methods--
also mildly intellectually

00:43:45.800 --> 00:43:49.460
interesting because how those
weak interactions manifest

00:43:49.460 --> 00:43:51.690
itself in vortices and all.

00:43:51.690 --> 00:43:53.580
It's really rich
and interesting.

00:43:53.580 --> 00:43:56.760
But the conceptional
problems appear

00:43:56.760 --> 00:43:59.560
when you go to
strong interactions.

00:43:59.560 --> 00:44:03.420
Strongly correlated matter is
where mean field descriptions

00:44:03.420 --> 00:44:04.430
no longer work.

00:44:04.430 --> 00:44:07.340
This is really the frontier
of our understanding

00:44:07.340 --> 00:44:08.440
of many-body systems.

00:44:08.440 --> 00:44:13.917
And when you want
to be there, you

00:44:13.917 --> 00:44:15.750
want to create a strongly
correlated system.

00:44:15.750 --> 00:44:19.020
And strongly correlated systems
means that the interaction

00:44:19.020 --> 00:44:23.330
energy dominates
over kinetic energy.

00:44:23.330 --> 00:44:25.300
In Bose-Einstein
condensates you can only

00:44:25.300 --> 00:44:28.360
go so far with
increasing interactions--

00:44:28.360 --> 00:44:30.210
why are Feshbach resonances?

00:44:30.210 --> 00:44:32.770
Because you get into some
inelastic collisions.

00:44:32.770 --> 00:44:34.080
So that's one knob to turn.

00:44:34.080 --> 00:44:36.490
You go to larger and larger
of scattering lengths,

00:44:36.490 --> 00:44:38.530
and crank up the interactions.

00:44:38.530 --> 00:44:42.600
But if atoms strongly interact,
they start to do bad chemistry.

00:44:42.600 --> 00:44:43.790
They start to spin flip.

00:44:43.790 --> 00:44:45.020
They do other things.

00:44:45.020 --> 00:44:47.410
And in some cases you
keep it under control.

00:44:47.410 --> 00:44:51.310
In others, you just can't
keep it under control.

00:44:51.310 --> 00:44:54.270
But another way to get
to strong interactions

00:44:54.270 --> 00:44:56.570
means you reduce
the kinetic energy.

00:44:56.570 --> 00:44:59.030
It's the ratio of the
two which matters.

00:44:59.030 --> 00:45:02.390
And when you put particles
in a lattice, well,

00:45:02.390 --> 00:45:05.410
the lattice actually
reduces the kinetic energy.

00:45:05.410 --> 00:45:07.200
You may know from
condensed matter physics

00:45:07.200 --> 00:45:09.500
that in a lattice there is
an effective mass, which

00:45:09.500 --> 00:45:11.520
is higher than the
[INAUDIBLE] mass.

00:45:11.520 --> 00:45:16.220
Therefore you've reduced
the kinetic energy.

00:45:16.220 --> 00:45:19.020
Or if you want another
hand-waving approximation,

00:45:19.020 --> 00:45:21.630
the kinetic energy is
given by the bandwidths.

00:45:21.630 --> 00:45:24.390
And if the tunneling
becomes slower and slower,

00:45:24.390 --> 00:45:26.580
the width of your
band becomes narrower,

00:45:26.580 --> 00:45:28.880
and your kinetic energy is less.

00:45:28.880 --> 00:45:31.800
So anyway, I can give you many
hand-waving approximations

00:45:31.800 --> 00:45:35.810
why in a lattice,
kinetic energy is reduced

00:45:35.810 --> 00:45:39.120
and repulsive energy
is probably enhanced,

00:45:39.120 --> 00:45:42.100
because instead of having
your atoms spread out,

00:45:42.100 --> 00:45:47.160
they're bunched up
at each lattice site

00:45:47.160 --> 00:45:49.960
into a higher density cloud.

00:45:49.960 --> 00:45:52.190
So anyway, maybe you're
interested in parity

00:45:52.190 --> 00:45:55.510
potentials, or you're
interested in quantum systems

00:45:55.510 --> 00:45:57.070
with strong correlations.

00:45:57.070 --> 00:46:01.590
For whatever reasons, you
want optical lattices.

00:46:01.590 --> 00:46:05.270
Now I have here a
few slides which

00:46:05.270 --> 00:46:09.280
introduce periodic
potentials, but it is really

00:46:09.280 --> 00:46:13.010
just the single particle
physics in a periodic potential.

00:46:13.010 --> 00:46:15.030
It has nothing do
with quantum gases.

00:46:15.030 --> 00:46:16.780
This could be the
first lecture of how

00:46:16.780 --> 00:46:20.230
to describe
electrons in a metal.

00:46:20.230 --> 00:46:22.330
So let me just quickly
go through assuming

00:46:22.330 --> 00:46:25.350
that almost all of
you are familiar.

00:46:25.350 --> 00:46:29.480
But I use those slides also just
to give you a few definitions

00:46:29.480 --> 00:46:31.850
and introduce a few symbols.

00:46:31.850 --> 00:46:36.050
So this is simple, boring,
exactly understood physics.

00:46:36.050 --> 00:46:39.090
We have a Hamiltonian
which has kinetic energy,

00:46:39.090 --> 00:46:43.170
and a periodic potential which
is our lattice potential.

00:46:43.170 --> 00:46:48.090
It's rather trivial to solve,
but exactly for your wave

00:46:48.090 --> 00:46:50.690
function, you use
Bloch's theorem

00:46:50.690 --> 00:46:54.260
and divide it by an exponential
factor with quasi momentum

00:46:54.260 --> 00:46:56.870
times a periodic function.

00:46:56.870 --> 00:47:00.180
And if you now solve
Schrodinger's equation,

00:47:00.180 --> 00:47:04.210
you want to use Fourier space.

00:47:04.210 --> 00:47:06.900
You Fourier analyze
the wave function.

00:47:06.900 --> 00:47:09.010
You Fourier analyze
the potential.

00:47:09.010 --> 00:47:12.730
And since the
potential is periodic,

00:47:12.730 --> 00:47:16.550
sine square potential has
only three Fourier components

00:47:16.550 --> 00:47:23.240
at 0 plus/minus 1 times the
periodicity of the lattice.

00:47:23.240 --> 00:47:28.800
You do a Fourier expansion for
your periodic wave function.

00:47:28.800 --> 00:47:32.480
And if you insert that into
Schrodinger's equation,

00:47:32.480 --> 00:47:35.600
well, the Fourier transform
has turned the differential

00:47:35.600 --> 00:47:39.120
equation into an
algebraic equation,

00:47:39.120 --> 00:47:41.380
because the second
derivative simply

00:47:41.380 --> 00:47:46.970
becomes now k
squared or q squared.

00:47:46.970 --> 00:47:50.245
So in other words, you have
a set of linear equations.

00:47:53.350 --> 00:47:55.630
There is an index
which is the band

00:47:55.630 --> 00:47:58.340
index-- how high
do you want to go?

00:47:58.340 --> 00:48:00.170
And usually you truncate it.

00:48:00.170 --> 00:48:01.360
But it's the same.

00:48:01.360 --> 00:48:03.730
It is that same
trivial story which

00:48:03.730 --> 00:48:07.620
is told in all textbooks of
condensed matter physics.

00:48:07.620 --> 00:48:11.810
If you have no band structure,
well, you have the parabola,

00:48:11.810 --> 00:48:13.570
but to prepare for
band structure,

00:48:13.570 --> 00:48:16.850
I've opened it down here in
the first Brillouin zone.

00:48:16.850 --> 00:48:19.250
And if you now
introduce a lattice,

00:48:19.250 --> 00:48:23.810
you introduce band gaps, and you
go from the left to the middle

00:48:23.810 --> 00:48:28.190
to the right for stronger
and stronger lattices.

00:48:28.190 --> 00:48:30.500
So the case which
I will focus on,

00:48:30.500 --> 00:48:35.610
because it is the most extreme
case away from free space,

00:48:35.610 --> 00:48:41.580
is this case which is called
the tight binding limit, where

00:48:41.580 --> 00:48:46.220
the potential energy of
the lattice is large.

00:48:46.220 --> 00:48:51.880
And large means compared
with the kinetic energy

00:48:51.880 --> 00:48:53.980
at the Brillouin
Zone, which is k

00:48:53.980 --> 00:48:57.170
squared-- k is the lattice
momentum-- k squared over 2 m.

00:48:57.170 --> 00:48:59.260
And that's the recoil energy.

00:48:59.260 --> 00:49:01.350
So that our dimensionless
parameter here

00:49:01.350 --> 00:49:04.880
is the depth of the
lattice measured

00:49:04.880 --> 00:49:09.000
in recoil energies
of the photon,

00:49:09.000 --> 00:49:10.650
because that is
the kinetic energy

00:49:10.650 --> 00:49:14.290
of the free gas at
the Brillouin zone.

00:49:14.290 --> 00:49:19.190
OK there are few things which
immediately simplify that.

00:49:19.190 --> 00:49:20.910
Once we're in the
tight binding limit,

00:49:20.910 --> 00:49:24.610
our lattice is really
deep, and each side

00:49:24.610 --> 00:49:26.710
forms a harmonic oscillator.

00:49:26.710 --> 00:49:28.530
And the harmonic
oscillator frequency

00:49:28.530 --> 00:49:32.650
is analytically given by
the depth of the lattice.

00:49:32.650 --> 00:49:37.150
And the solution here
for the lowest band

00:49:37.150 --> 00:49:40.190
is that the lowest
band-- the energy

00:49:40.190 --> 00:49:43.780
in the lowest band, the
dispersion relation is-- well,

00:49:43.780 --> 00:49:47.170
we have a harmonic oscillator
in each site at x y z.

00:49:47.170 --> 00:49:49.810
So the average energy
in the lowest band

00:49:49.810 --> 00:49:54.940
is the 0 point energy in x, y,
and z-- three half h-bar omega

00:49:54.940 --> 00:49:56.000
0.

00:49:56.000 --> 00:49:59.780
And then we have a
cosinusoidal band structure

00:49:59.780 --> 00:50:02.570
where q is the quasimomentum.

00:50:02.570 --> 00:50:05.930
And what appears here as the
only interesting parameter

00:50:05.930 --> 00:50:07.600
is j.

00:50:07.600 --> 00:50:15.990
And j is I think this 4
should be 4j is the bandwidth.

00:50:19.850 --> 00:50:23.310
So what appears here now
for the first time is j.

00:50:23.310 --> 00:50:26.030
It appears here
as the bandwidth.

00:50:26.030 --> 00:50:30.250
But let me immediately give
it another interpretation

00:50:30.250 --> 00:50:34.940
as a tunneling matrix element in
the following way-- right now,

00:50:34.940 --> 00:50:39.030
we have formulated the physics
in Bloch wave functions

00:50:39.030 --> 00:50:41.150
which are infinitely extended.

00:50:41.150 --> 00:50:43.580
The Bloch wave functions
are for the lattice

00:50:43.580 --> 00:50:46.770
what plain waves
are for free space.

00:50:46.770 --> 00:50:50.780
But if you have
tight binding limit,

00:50:50.780 --> 00:50:52.860
there is another limit
which is important.

00:50:52.860 --> 00:50:58.340
Namely, a particle is localized
and hops around in the lattice.

00:50:58.340 --> 00:51:02.130
The localized particle, of
course, is in free space.

00:51:02.130 --> 00:51:06.540
It would be a wave packet-- a
superposition of plain waves.

00:51:06.540 --> 00:51:08.490
So let's do the
same in the lattice.

00:51:08.490 --> 00:51:12.060
Let's construct
superpositions of Bloch waves.

00:51:12.060 --> 00:51:13.910
And these are our wave packets.

00:51:13.910 --> 00:51:17.420
And the wave packet is now
called the Wannier function.

00:51:17.420 --> 00:51:20.510
And there is a
mathematical procedure

00:51:20.510 --> 00:51:22.530
how you should pick
the phases here

00:51:22.530 --> 00:51:24.710
to get the maximal
normalization.

00:51:24.710 --> 00:51:28.210
But the simple picture is
those Wannier functions are

00:51:28.210 --> 00:51:31.730
very, very close to the
Gaussian ground state

00:51:31.730 --> 00:51:35.050
solution of the harmonic
oscillator on each side.

00:51:35.050 --> 00:51:39.080
The wings are different, but
I don't want to go into that.

00:51:39.080 --> 00:51:43.740
You transform from an
orthonormal basis of Bloch wave

00:51:43.740 --> 00:51:48.630
function to another orthonormal
basis Wannier function.

00:51:48.630 --> 00:51:53.760
And the Wannier functions are
as well localized as possible.

00:51:53.760 --> 00:51:55.800
That's the procedure.

00:51:55.800 --> 00:51:59.970
And now we can simply
rewrite our total Hamiltonian

00:51:59.970 --> 00:52:03.385
or everything we're interested
in, not in Bloch wave functions

00:52:03.385 --> 00:52:06.960
but in Wannier wave functions.

00:52:06.960 --> 00:52:12.250
And what comes out now is,
is that the bandwidth j

00:52:12.250 --> 00:52:17.860
is nothing else than our
Hamiltonian with kinetic energy

00:52:17.860 --> 00:52:19.540
in the periodic potential.

00:52:19.540 --> 00:52:22.600
But j becomes now
a matrix element

00:52:22.600 --> 00:52:24.040
between two Wannier functions.

00:52:27.690 --> 00:52:31.990
But the Wannier
functions have now-- I'll

00:52:31.990 --> 00:52:34.010
put in some indices
in a moment--

00:52:34.010 --> 00:52:36.890
connect now two different sides.

00:52:36.890 --> 00:52:39.540
So it is-- you have
Wannier function.

00:52:39.540 --> 00:52:41.760
You have the Hamiltonian
and connect it

00:52:41.760 --> 00:52:43.690
to another Wannier function.

00:52:43.690 --> 00:52:49.050
So it is the amplitude
that, with the Hamiltonian,

00:52:49.050 --> 00:52:52.890
the particle can hop from
one side to another side.

00:52:52.890 --> 00:52:56.390
So therefore j, which
was the bandwidth,

00:52:56.390 --> 00:52:59.890
is now the tunneling
energy divided

00:52:59.890 --> 00:53:03.020
by h bar-- the tunneling
rate from on one side

00:53:03.020 --> 00:53:05.910
to the other side.

00:53:05.910 --> 00:53:08.100
For very deep lattice,
everything is analytic

00:53:08.100 --> 00:53:11.460
and it can easily be solved.

00:53:11.460 --> 00:53:14.210
And I mentioned already in the
tight binding approximation,

00:53:14.210 --> 00:53:16.060
you should think about
your Wannier function

00:53:16.060 --> 00:53:19.310
as just localized
Gaussian eigensolutions

00:53:19.310 --> 00:53:22.070
of the harmonic oscillator.

00:53:22.070 --> 00:53:24.190
Yes?

00:53:24.190 --> 00:53:28.660
AUDIENCE: So qualitatively, this
question sounds sort of silly,

00:53:28.660 --> 00:53:32.140
but normally when we write
down the solution for j,

00:53:32.140 --> 00:53:35.810
we're only considering
nearest neighbor.

00:53:35.810 --> 00:53:39.275
But from the math,
I don't immediately

00:53:39.275 --> 00:53:44.230
see why we wouldn't
include i equal to j.

00:53:44.230 --> 00:53:46.790
PROFESSOR: Give
me one more slide.

00:53:46.790 --> 00:53:53.870
So I should've
actually-- what I should

00:53:53.870 --> 00:53:57.920
have done is that--
j has an index here.

00:53:57.920 --> 00:54:02.580
I just didn't want to
overload you with indices.

00:54:02.580 --> 00:54:04.330
I mean, this is sort
of just telling you

00:54:04.330 --> 00:54:07.010
what j is in its simplest form.

00:54:07.010 --> 00:54:10.610
It is loaded with indices and
I well show you in a moment

00:54:10.610 --> 00:54:12.780
where those indices come in.

00:54:12.780 --> 00:54:14.920
So I just wanted to
give you the idea

00:54:14.920 --> 00:54:17.750
if we want to have
Wannier function.

00:54:17.750 --> 00:54:20.850
We hop from one Wannier
function to the other one,

00:54:20.850 --> 00:54:23.060
and the operator
is the Hamiltonian.

00:54:23.060 --> 00:54:28.840
And therefore, there
should be an index j and l.

00:54:28.840 --> 00:54:34.280
And maybe-- let me just do the
next step first and then come

00:54:34.280 --> 00:54:36.030
back to it, but I
wanted to tell you here

00:54:36.030 --> 00:54:39.040
what I'm aiming at--
namely interpretation of j,

00:54:39.040 --> 00:54:41.460
of tunneling from
one side to the next.

00:54:41.460 --> 00:54:47.400
But right now I haven't really
told you which j I really mean.

00:54:47.400 --> 00:54:49.930
There should be-- based
on the right-hand side,

00:54:49.930 --> 00:54:53.040
there is a j which
has two indices.

00:54:53.040 --> 00:54:56.480
And I will make the indices
disappear in a moment.

00:54:56.480 --> 00:54:59.730
But before I make those
indices disappear,

00:54:59.730 --> 00:55:03.350
let me introduce the other
relevant parameter, which

00:55:03.350 --> 00:55:05.850
will also have
indices, and that is we

00:55:05.850 --> 00:55:08.540
have to bring in
the interactions.

00:55:08.540 --> 00:55:11.150
We want to describe
an interacting system.

00:55:11.150 --> 00:55:13.680
We describe an
interacting system

00:55:13.680 --> 00:55:15.490
using the short-range
approximation

00:55:15.490 --> 00:55:20.690
by assuming that two particles
interact with a delta function.

00:55:20.690 --> 00:55:26.360
And if you have two particles
on site, each of them

00:55:26.360 --> 00:55:30.370
has a density which is the
Wannier function squared.

00:55:30.370 --> 00:55:33.950
And the product of the
two densities integrated

00:55:33.950 --> 00:55:38.910
gives us the expectation value
for the repulsive energy.

00:55:38.910 --> 00:55:41.440
And this is given here.

00:55:41.440 --> 00:55:44.000
So the moment we
introduce interactions,

00:55:44.000 --> 00:55:50.820
we are now interested in
the interaction energy

00:55:50.820 --> 00:55:57.150
between two particles which in
this case occupy the same side.

00:55:57.150 --> 00:56:01.010
OK so I've tried to introduce
was what sort of j is.

00:56:01.010 --> 00:56:03.730
j is a matrix element
between two Wannier functions

00:56:03.730 --> 00:56:05.750
with a Hamiltonian in between.

00:56:05.750 --> 00:56:10.430
And u is the matrix element
of two Wannier functions

00:56:10.430 --> 00:56:13.730
with the interaction
operator in between.

00:56:13.730 --> 00:56:15.860
And now I want to
use that concept

00:56:15.860 --> 00:56:21.200
to take my full
Hamiltonian and transform

00:56:21.200 --> 00:56:26.570
from field operators localized
at x to Wannier functions.

00:56:26.570 --> 00:56:29.650
So they B operators are
now creation operators.

00:56:29.650 --> 00:56:31.820
They create an atom
in a Wannier function.

00:56:31.820 --> 00:56:34.920
In other words, B
dagger means you

00:56:34.920 --> 00:56:38.370
have a particle in a
Wannier function at site i.

00:56:38.370 --> 00:56:40.380
And I just use that as
a basis transformation

00:56:40.380 --> 00:56:42.380
and the exact transformation
of this Hamiltonian

00:56:42.380 --> 00:56:47.250
is now into this form.

00:56:47.250 --> 00:56:47.750
So

00:56:47.750 --> 00:56:52.850
What I have right now is, I have
the tunneling matrix element

00:56:52.850 --> 00:56:54.570
between particles
at site i and j,

00:56:54.570 --> 00:56:57.140
and I have to sum
over all of them.

00:56:57.140 --> 00:57:15.060
And in terms of interaction,
I can calculate this matrix

00:57:15.060 --> 00:57:17.620
element by using Wannier
function with four

00:57:17.620 --> 00:57:21.540
different indices
and ask what happens.

00:57:21.540 --> 00:57:24.880
And this is simply an
exact way of rewriting it.

00:57:24.880 --> 00:57:27.190
And here I've given
you the definition.

00:57:27.190 --> 00:57:28.720
So if you want to
forget everything

00:57:28.720 --> 00:57:34.800
I told you about j and u, I've
done an exact transformation

00:57:34.800 --> 00:57:38.490
from field operators to Wannier
function creation operators.

00:57:38.490 --> 00:57:45.050
And this introduces tunneling
terms like this from site i

00:57:45.050 --> 00:57:47.070
to site j.

00:57:47.070 --> 00:57:51.940
And these here includes products
of four Wannier functions

00:57:51.940 --> 00:57:55.370
which are responsible
for the interaction term.

00:57:55.370 --> 00:57:57.960
Actually, if this is
not complicated enough,

00:57:57.960 --> 00:57:59.670
I've suppressed
band indices here.

00:57:59.670 --> 00:58:03.050
I should also now sum
over all possible bands.

00:58:03.050 --> 00:58:07.540
But OK, I want to come now
to the leading approximation

00:58:07.540 --> 00:58:09.020
in a tight binding model.

00:58:09.020 --> 00:58:11.210
And that is where--
I mean those Wannier

00:58:11.210 --> 00:58:12.910
functions are overlapped.

00:58:12.910 --> 00:58:15.770
Two neighboring Wannier
functions barely overlap.

00:58:15.770 --> 00:58:19.050
If I go further away, the
overlap becomes even smaller.

00:58:19.050 --> 00:58:22.950
So the most dominant terms are
nearest neighbor interactions.

00:58:22.950 --> 00:58:24.450
And the nearest
neighbor interaction

00:58:24.450 --> 00:58:27.230
is where i and j differ by 1.

00:58:27.230 --> 00:58:30.440
And this is what I
call j without indices.

00:58:30.440 --> 00:58:35.970
And similarly, when it comes
to the interaction term

00:58:35.970 --> 00:58:40.620
where we have products
of four Wannier functions

00:58:40.620 --> 00:58:44.020
and we want to get the
overlap of all four,

00:58:44.020 --> 00:58:47.650
and then multiply it with g,
the prefactor of our delta

00:58:47.650 --> 00:58:50.260
function to get an
interaction term,

00:58:50.260 --> 00:58:54.530
well the best overlap is if
all indices are the same.

00:58:54.530 --> 00:58:56.780
And this is what I call U.

00:58:56.780 --> 00:59:00.750
So in that limit, in
that tight binding limit,

00:59:00.750 --> 00:59:03.300
my Hamiltonian is
now very simple.

00:59:03.300 --> 00:59:08.530
It consists of a tunneling
term parametrized with j,

00:59:08.530 --> 00:59:16.470
and an on site interaction
term parametrized with U. Yes.

00:59:16.470 --> 00:59:19.830
AUDIENCE: So you're saying
i, j and k are all the same,

00:59:19.830 --> 00:59:22.710
so the interaction
is with itself?

00:59:26.550 --> 00:59:29.790
PROFESSOR: No, two
particles per site.

00:59:29.790 --> 00:59:32.460
When the four
particles are the same,

00:59:32.460 --> 00:59:40.590
it turns into-- this
Hamiltonian here has

00:59:40.590 --> 00:59:42.510
all indices are the same.

00:59:42.510 --> 00:59:49.680
And if you calculate that, it
turns into the product of 2 b.

00:59:49.680 --> 00:59:53.520
b dagger is the occupation
number at each site.

00:59:53.520 --> 00:59:55.690
But if you're careful
with commutators,

00:59:55.690 --> 00:59:58.980
it becomes occupation number
times occupation number

00:59:58.980 --> 01:00:00.140
minus 1.

01:00:00.140 --> 01:00:03.700
If you have only one particle
per site, this term is 0.

01:00:03.700 --> 01:00:09.930
So technically U is, if
you put in 2 times 1,

01:00:09.930 --> 01:00:11.980
if you have two
particles per site,

01:00:11.980 --> 01:00:15.460
U is the interaction energy
between two particles.

01:00:15.460 --> 01:00:17.240
Just use this
expression to figure out

01:00:17.240 --> 01:00:18.740
what it is for three or four.

01:00:18.740 --> 01:00:21.280
But for one particle, you get 0.

01:00:21.280 --> 01:00:25.230
The self interaction of a
particle is absolutely 0.

01:00:25.230 --> 01:00:27.235
One particle does not
interact with itself.

01:00:31.029 --> 01:00:33.570
AUDIENCE: That gets back to my
question with the [INAUDIBLE].

01:00:33.570 --> 01:00:40.120
So when you have i equals j, the
[INAUDIBLE] term, do you just--

01:00:40.120 --> 01:00:43.670
PROFESSOR: No, I assume,
i j is nearest neighbor.

01:00:43.670 --> 01:00:46.966
I assume that the index
i and j differ by 1.

01:00:46.966 --> 01:00:49.215
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I mean your
argument was that the best

01:00:49.215 --> 01:00:50.915
overlap is between
nearest neighbors.

01:00:50.915 --> 01:00:51.540
PROFESSOR: Yes.

01:00:54.100 --> 01:00:57.390
AUDIENCE: So an overlap
with the Wannier functions

01:00:57.390 --> 01:01:01.145
at the same site is sort
of the kinetic energy term.

01:01:01.145 --> 01:01:04.070
Is it approximately 0,
or you just absorb that

01:01:04.070 --> 01:01:06.310
