01:02:43.160 --> 01:02:43.660
Thanks.

01:02:43.660 --> 01:02:46.530
It was good to clarify it.

01:02:46.530 --> 01:02:50.680
OK, I think within
the next 20 minutes,

01:02:50.680 --> 01:02:53.986
I can step you through
the superfluid to Mott

01:02:53.986 --> 01:02:54.860
insulator transition.

01:02:57.490 --> 01:03:03.100
First, references for what
I've just said are given here.

01:03:05.670 --> 01:03:11.940
But let me now come take
this Bose-Hubbard model

01:03:11.940 --> 01:03:15.930
and discuss its
two limiting cases.

01:03:15.930 --> 01:03:19.560
One case is where U
is much larger than j.

01:03:19.560 --> 01:03:22.500
The other case is where
j is much larger than U.

01:03:22.500 --> 01:03:24.740
These are the two
limiting cases,

01:03:24.740 --> 01:03:27.820
and it will turn out
that one is an insulator

01:03:27.820 --> 01:03:29.980
and one is a superfluid.

01:03:29.980 --> 01:03:32.150
And that makes perfect
sense, of course.

01:03:32.150 --> 01:03:37.040
If U is much larger than
j, I can set j equals to 0

01:03:37.040 --> 01:03:38.410
if I can neglect it.

01:03:38.410 --> 01:03:42.330
No tunneling means no transport,
and that means an insulator.

01:03:42.330 --> 01:03:47.250
It's also clear that when
there is no tunneling,

01:03:47.250 --> 01:03:50.720
that the system is
really described

01:03:50.720 --> 01:03:55.690
by a product of so and so
many particles per site.

01:03:55.690 --> 01:03:58.260
So it could be one
particle per site.

01:03:58.260 --> 01:04:00.020
And I have a product
over all sites,

01:04:00.020 --> 01:04:03.270
or two particles per site.

01:04:03.270 --> 01:04:05.010
So this will be
the ground state.

01:04:05.010 --> 01:04:08.610
And it's called the ground
state of the Mott insulator.

01:04:08.610 --> 01:04:10.610
It's also trivial
to discuss what

01:04:10.610 --> 01:04:13.050
happens if j is much,
much larger than U,

01:04:13.050 --> 01:04:17.620
because then I simply neglect
U, and I have a free gas.

01:04:17.620 --> 01:04:20.300
Well, a free gas of
Bloch wave function,

01:04:20.300 --> 01:04:26.910
but that's the same as a free
gas of planar wave function.

01:04:26.910 --> 01:04:30.600
It's just that quasimomentum
replaces momentum.

01:04:30.600 --> 01:04:32.950
And if you have just
an ideal Bose gas

01:04:32.950 --> 01:04:36.490
in a periodic lattice instead
of Bose-Einstein condensation

01:04:36.490 --> 01:04:38.520
in the lowest
momentum state, you

01:04:38.520 --> 01:04:41.490
have Bose-Einstein condensation
in the lowest quasimomentum

01:04:41.490 --> 01:04:43.480
state.

01:04:43.480 --> 01:04:46.400
The lowest quasimomentum
state is a superposition

01:04:46.400 --> 01:04:49.170
of all Wannier
function-- I mean,

01:04:49.170 --> 01:04:51.580
the 0 momentum
state in free space

01:04:51.580 --> 01:04:57.830
is a superposition of all
position delta functions.

01:04:57.830 --> 01:04:59.870
The plane wave is delocalized.

01:04:59.870 --> 01:05:01.740
And the lowest
quasimomentum state

01:05:01.740 --> 01:05:06.290
is just completely delocalized
over all Wannier functions.

01:05:06.290 --> 01:05:07.910
But this is nothing
else than the q

01:05:07.910 --> 01:05:11.660
equals 0 quasimomentum
Bloch wave.

01:05:11.660 --> 01:05:13.410
The interesting
question is-- and this

01:05:13.410 --> 01:05:17.270
has led to hundreds if not
more papers in the literature--

01:05:17.270 --> 01:05:21.230
how do we go from one
limit to the other limit?

01:05:21.230 --> 01:05:23.690
And now you would
say, well, maybe we

01:05:23.690 --> 01:05:25.850
should use what
has worked so well.

01:05:25.850 --> 01:05:28.490
We should use the
Bogoliubov approximation.

01:05:28.490 --> 01:05:30.330
Just assume we
have a condensate,

01:05:30.330 --> 01:05:36.580
replace all those kind of a 0
operators for the lowest Bloch

01:05:36.580 --> 01:05:37.610
waves.

01:05:37.610 --> 01:05:41.390
However, this doesn't work,
because the interesting thing

01:05:41.390 --> 01:05:44.750
here is to find the
transition from the superfluid

01:05:44.750 --> 01:05:46.125
from the Bose-Einstein
condensate

01:05:46.125 --> 01:05:48.710
to an insulating state.

01:05:48.710 --> 01:05:50.800
The nature of this
approximation is

01:05:50.800 --> 01:05:52.960
that you need N 0 to be large.

01:05:52.960 --> 01:05:58.200
But we're interested when the
condensate wave function turns

01:05:58.200 --> 01:06:01.670
to 0, and in the
insulator it becomes 0.

01:06:01.670 --> 01:06:04.970
So we are actually interested
in the opposite limit.

01:06:04.970 --> 01:06:06.950
And indeed, if you
would ignore everything

01:06:06.950 --> 01:06:08.590
I've just said that
doesn't make sense

01:06:08.590 --> 01:06:11.260
to make this approximation
and make it nevertheless,

01:06:11.260 --> 01:06:14.500
you will find that you never
get the insulating state

01:06:14.500 --> 01:06:17.200
because you've pretty much
eliminated the possibility

01:06:17.200 --> 01:06:21.316
to describe an insulating state
by doing this approximation.

01:06:21.316 --> 01:06:22.690
So I want to show
you now that we

01:06:22.690 --> 01:06:25.680
have to do another mean
field approximation, which

01:06:25.680 --> 01:06:27.800
is actually nice.

01:06:27.800 --> 01:06:32.890
It's very different from this
Bogoliubov approximation,

01:06:32.890 --> 01:06:34.850
but it's also a mean
field approximation

01:06:34.850 --> 01:06:37.830
which will describe our system.

01:06:37.830 --> 01:06:43.010
So the goal is now
that I want to find

01:06:43.010 --> 01:06:47.540
an effective Hamiltonian
which describes

01:06:47.540 --> 01:06:50.090
the transition
from here to there.

01:06:50.090 --> 01:06:53.190
And the important
approximation I will use

01:06:53.190 --> 01:06:58.300
was is the following-- again,
I have to get rid of operators.

01:06:58.300 --> 01:07:01.500
Products of two many
operators cannot be solved.

01:07:01.500 --> 01:07:05.290
And so what I will do is I
will use products of operators,

01:07:05.290 --> 01:07:08.960
write them as average
value plus fluctuations.

01:07:08.960 --> 01:07:11.730
And then when I
multiply that out,

01:07:11.730 --> 01:07:15.240
I take the product of
the average values,

01:07:15.240 --> 01:07:19.050
and I include the
fluctuations in leading order.

01:07:19.050 --> 01:07:23.370
So I take delta A times B
and delta B times A average,

01:07:23.370 --> 01:07:27.360
but I neglect the product
of those fluctuations.

01:07:27.360 --> 01:07:31.070
You can say I neglect the
correlation of fluctuations

01:07:31.070 --> 01:07:33.480
here.

01:07:33.480 --> 01:07:36.240
So this is spelled out here.

01:07:36.240 --> 01:07:40.870
But the sign is important.

01:07:40.870 --> 01:07:45.390
Just look at this equation--
A delta B plus delta B with B

01:07:45.390 --> 01:07:48.440
plus A average times B average.

01:07:48.440 --> 01:07:55.920
If I absorb A times B by
upgrading delta B to B,

01:07:55.920 --> 01:07:59.170
but I do the same here,
I have to subtract

01:07:59.170 --> 01:08:01.780
1 product of the
two average values.

01:08:01.780 --> 01:08:05.510
It's actually this minus sign
which will play a role later,

01:08:05.510 --> 01:08:09.110
but here you see already that
I will make this decoupling

01:08:09.110 --> 01:08:11.600
approximation-- that I
decouple the fluctuations

01:08:11.600 --> 01:08:14.160
from each other and I
write it in this way,

01:08:14.160 --> 01:08:16.240
there is an
important minus sign.

01:08:18.859 --> 01:08:24.000
OK, so we want to start
in the insulating state.

01:08:24.000 --> 01:08:27.620
And we're going to figure out
how does the system develop

01:08:27.620 --> 01:08:30.569
superfluidity out of
the insulation state?

01:08:30.569 --> 01:08:33.110
And the perturbation
operator which takes me out

01:08:33.110 --> 01:08:37.290
of the insulating
state is tunneling.

01:08:37.290 --> 01:08:41.470
So therefore, the operator which
is responsible for breaking out

01:08:41.470 --> 01:08:44.890
of the insulating
state is the operator

01:08:44.890 --> 01:08:49.060
which induces tunneling
between neighboring sites.

01:08:49.060 --> 01:08:51.890
And the tunneling operator
in this Hamiltonian--

01:08:51.890 --> 01:08:56.580
remember, the Bose-Hubbard
model had j times B dagger B--

01:08:56.580 --> 01:09:00.550
this was our tunneling
term-- this involves now

01:09:00.550 --> 01:09:02.240
products of operators.

01:09:02.240 --> 01:09:05.330
And I told you we want to get
rid of products of operators

01:09:05.330 --> 01:09:07.470
to get something we
can easily solve.

01:09:07.470 --> 01:09:10.370
So we use now this
product of operators

01:09:10.370 --> 01:09:14.310
on two neighboring sites.

01:09:14.310 --> 01:09:20.660
And we use exactly this
decoupling approximation.

01:09:20.660 --> 01:09:26.210
So therefore, we replace each
operator by an average value,

01:09:26.210 --> 01:09:28.880
and we neglect the product
of the fluctuations.

01:09:28.880 --> 01:09:30.899
And then we obtain this.

01:09:30.899 --> 01:09:34.750
And I explained to you where
the minus sign came from.

01:09:34.750 --> 01:09:45.659
So now I call this average
value of the operator B l,

01:09:45.659 --> 01:09:48.529
I call the superfluid
order parameter psi.

01:09:54.380 --> 01:09:56.820
I think I could have
chosen psi to be complex,

01:09:56.820 --> 01:10:01.410
and then B l dagger B l
would have complex conjugate.

01:10:01.410 --> 01:10:05.450
But it's sufficient here
to restrict the discussion

01:10:05.450 --> 01:10:08.690
on real numbers, and it
makes the notation simpler.

01:10:08.690 --> 01:10:12.040
So anyway, I introduce that.

01:10:12.040 --> 01:10:15.650
And what happens now
is the following--

01:10:15.650 --> 01:10:19.770
that I have my Hamiltonian.

01:10:19.770 --> 01:10:23.510
The Hamiltonian had
the interaction energy.

01:10:28.460 --> 01:10:33.110
But the tunneling term
is now very simplified,

01:10:33.110 --> 01:10:35.520
because instead of
tunneling from one site

01:10:35.520 --> 01:10:39.660
to a neighboring
site, the other side

01:10:39.660 --> 01:10:42.640
is sort of absorbed
by the mean field,

01:10:42.640 --> 01:10:45.730
by the superfluid
order parameter psi.

01:10:45.730 --> 01:10:51.470
And therefore, and this
here gives me a psi

01:10:51.470 --> 01:10:55.270
squared term which appears here.

01:10:55.270 --> 01:10:58.720
Trust me, this is just
an identical rewrite

01:10:58.720 --> 01:11:02.850
of the previous Hamiltonian
by using this decoupling

01:11:02.850 --> 01:11:05.160
approximation.

01:11:05.160 --> 01:11:09.860
So what we have gained now
is something really dramatic.

01:11:09.860 --> 01:11:13.540
We had many sites and
tunneling from site to site.

01:11:13.540 --> 01:11:20.020
But if you look at
it now, we simply sum

01:11:20.020 --> 01:11:23.850
the effective Hamiltonian
over site index l.

01:11:23.850 --> 01:11:26.460
So our effective
Hamiltonian is now

01:11:26.460 --> 01:11:29.950
the sum of an identical
Hamiltonian per site.

01:11:29.950 --> 01:11:32.760
The sites no longer
interact with each other.

01:11:32.760 --> 01:11:37.930
Each site interacts with all
the other sites described

01:11:37.930 --> 01:11:41.530
by the mean field by the
superfluid order parameter psi.

01:11:41.530 --> 01:11:43.800
So therefore, our
many-body problem,

01:11:43.800 --> 01:11:45.380
which is still a
many-body problem,

01:11:45.380 --> 01:11:49.720
but has turned into an effective
Hamiltonian for each site,

01:11:49.720 --> 01:11:52.910
because each side has
the same Hamiltonian.

01:11:52.910 --> 01:11:53.410
Colin.

01:11:53.410 --> 01:11:57.730
AUDIENCE: What happened
to the j psi squared term?

01:11:57.730 --> 01:12:00.132
PROFESSOR: This here?

01:12:00.132 --> 01:12:00.840
AUDIENCE: Oh, OK.

01:12:04.640 --> 01:12:08.740
PROFESSOR: OK so I can say
instead of solving for the sum,

01:12:08.740 --> 01:12:11.850
I can just solve for
each site individually.

01:12:11.850 --> 01:12:17.780
And this is now my effective
Hamiltonian for each site.

01:12:17.780 --> 01:12:23.510
Now I want to catch the
onset of superfluidity.

01:12:23.510 --> 01:12:27.240
So I want to get the
system when psi is small.

01:12:27.240 --> 01:12:30.690
And therefore, I can just
ask-- I don't know what psi is.

01:12:30.690 --> 01:12:32.060
It's part of my solution.

01:12:32.060 --> 01:12:34.290
But I'm interested
in the moment when

01:12:34.290 --> 01:12:39.720
psi begins to take off from
0, when superfluidity emerges.

01:12:39.720 --> 01:12:45.280
So what I can therefore do is,
I can regard psi as an epsilon

01:12:45.280 --> 01:12:47.930
parameter, as a small parameter.

01:12:47.930 --> 01:12:52.310
And the psi parameter
comes with an operator V.

01:12:52.310 --> 01:12:57.700
And this operator V is nothing
else than B l dagger plus B l.

01:12:57.700 --> 01:13:00.030
So in other words,
what I'm doing is,

01:13:00.030 --> 01:13:04.370
I'm separating my Hamiltonian
into a Hamiltonian which

01:13:04.370 --> 01:13:06.960
is diagonal in the
quantum numbers

01:13:06.960 --> 01:13:09.680
of the isolating state--
just one, two, three

01:13:09.680 --> 01:13:11.600
particles per site.

01:13:11.600 --> 01:13:13.340
And psi squared is the Z number.

01:13:13.340 --> 01:13:17.170
Psi squared is also
diagonal in that.

01:13:17.170 --> 01:13:19.560
And now the possibility
of tunneling,

01:13:19.560 --> 01:13:22.720
the possibility of
superfluidity is now

01:13:22.720 --> 01:13:29.610
perturbative in this
term psi times V.

01:13:29.610 --> 01:13:33.460
OK, I don't want to explain,
actually, this expression.

01:13:33.460 --> 01:13:37.020
It just formalizes
[INAUDIBLE] intermediate step.

01:13:37.020 --> 01:13:38.970
When we have the
chemical potential,

01:13:38.970 --> 01:13:41.380
and we raise the
chemical potential--

01:13:41.380 --> 01:13:44.330
we go from zero to
one particle per site

01:13:44.330 --> 01:13:45.950
to two particles per site.

01:13:45.950 --> 01:13:48.180
And whatever the
chemical potential is

01:13:48.180 --> 01:13:51.410
determines whether we have
one or two particles per site.

01:13:51.410 --> 01:13:56.350
This is just telling me as a
function of chemical potential,

01:13:56.350 --> 01:13:59.550
what is the ground
state of the insulator?

01:13:59.550 --> 01:14:01.960
So now we take this ground
state-- it's actually

01:14:01.960 --> 01:14:04.240
much easier described
in words then

01:14:04.240 --> 01:14:07.210
by this formula-- we
take this ground state

01:14:07.210 --> 01:14:14.900
and do perturbation theory in
our term psi times V. Remember,

01:14:14.900 --> 01:14:20.620
the operator is B dagger
B. And the epsilon is psi.

01:14:20.620 --> 01:14:26.220
So in second-order perturbation
theory, we get psi squared.

01:14:26.220 --> 01:14:30.480
And then V, because B B
dagger, is very simple.

01:14:30.480 --> 01:14:37.490
It only couples one occupation
number N to N plus 1

01:14:37.490 --> 01:14:40.440
and N minus 1,
because B and B dagger

01:14:40.440 --> 01:14:43.120
destroy or create a
particle per site.

01:14:43.120 --> 01:14:47.520
So therefore, I can
immediately write down

01:14:47.520 --> 01:14:50.830
what this matrix element is
in second-order perturbation

01:14:50.830 --> 01:14:52.570
theory.

01:14:52.570 --> 01:14:54.930
I mean, these are all--
sorry, it's all defined here.

01:14:54.930 --> 01:14:57.020
I know I'm losing you now.

01:14:57.020 --> 01:15:00.970
Nobody will tell me what is the
difference between U bar and U,

01:15:00.970 --> 01:15:03.950
but it's trivially defined.

01:15:03.950 --> 01:15:07.330
So the idea is we have
the isolating system.

01:15:07.330 --> 01:15:10.020
We do perturbation
theory in tunneling.

01:15:10.020 --> 01:15:17.180
And the perturbative operator
is psi times B plus B dagger.

01:15:17.180 --> 01:15:19.160
The B plus B dagger
matrix elements

01:15:19.160 --> 01:15:22.555
are trivial, because
they admix to N particles

01:15:22.555 --> 01:15:25.450
per site-- N plus
1 and N minus 1.

01:15:25.450 --> 01:15:27.794
And this is what
we've done here.

01:15:27.794 --> 01:15:29.710
AUDIENCE: And the j is
just occupation number?

01:15:29.710 --> 01:15:34.259
PROFESSOR: The j is the
occupation number of our site.

01:15:34.259 --> 01:15:35.550
AUDIENCE: I have two questions.

01:15:35.550 --> 01:15:41.044
So in the bottom equation, what
happened to the psi squared?

01:15:41.044 --> 01:15:42.460
PROFESSOR: Sorry,
this is the sum.

01:15:42.460 --> 01:15:44.394
The psi square is missing.

01:15:44.394 --> 01:15:46.804
AUDIENCE: I guess I
had the same question

01:15:46.804 --> 01:15:50.184
for the equation next
to the green thing.

01:15:50.184 --> 01:15:52.860
Is there supposed to be
a psi squared in there?

01:15:52.860 --> 01:15:56.360
Because originally, there's
a psi squared and an h0.

01:15:56.360 --> 01:15:59.090
PROFESSOR: No, this is the
ground state where psi is 0.

01:15:59.090 --> 01:16:00.600
And now we do
perturbation theory

01:16:00.600 --> 01:16:05.500
in psi V. These are the
unperturbed energies which

01:16:05.500 --> 01:16:07.640
appear in the
energy denominator.

01:16:07.640 --> 01:16:09.530
The wave functions
we are using are

01:16:09.530 --> 01:16:12.280
Fock states-- number
states-- per site.

01:16:12.280 --> 01:16:17.070
And here we couple occupation
number j to all possible N's.

01:16:17.070 --> 01:16:21.050
But because of B and B dagger,
N has only two values--

01:16:21.050 --> 01:16:22.741
j plus 1 and j minus 1.

01:16:22.741 --> 01:16:23.990
And this is what's given here.

01:16:26.680 --> 01:16:28.270
It's mathematically trivial.

01:16:28.270 --> 01:16:31.820
The notation is more complicated
than the physics behind it.

01:16:31.820 --> 01:16:36.110
But now comes again-- I think I
need five minutes and I'm done.

01:16:36.110 --> 01:16:37.920
But now comes the
interesting physics.

01:16:37.920 --> 01:16:41.080
We have to ask what
are we doing here?

01:16:41.080 --> 01:16:44.720
It's all the mathematical, and
the math is really simple here.

01:16:44.720 --> 01:16:48.860
What we have done is we have
looked at the isolating state,

01:16:48.860 --> 01:16:53.700
and we have done perturbation
theory in psi times B plus B

01:16:53.700 --> 01:16:54.770
dagger.

01:16:54.770 --> 01:16:56.710
And now we get an
energy correction

01:16:56.710 --> 01:16:59.760
which is psi squared.

01:16:59.760 --> 01:17:03.300
And what are we
really doing here?

01:17:03.300 --> 01:17:05.440
Well, you can say
the following--

01:17:05.440 --> 01:17:07.330
we started with a
hypothesis that we

01:17:07.330 --> 01:17:11.720
have a superfluid state
characterized by psi and psi,

01:17:11.720 --> 01:17:14.300
at the onset of
superfluidity-- is small.

01:17:14.300 --> 01:17:16.210
But now we have
done the calculation

01:17:16.210 --> 01:17:18.590
assuming that there is a psi.

01:17:18.590 --> 01:17:21.370
But now we are turning around
and said have we really

01:17:21.370 --> 01:17:24.450
done the system a favor by
introducing superfluidity?

01:17:24.450 --> 01:17:27.810
In other words, has our
perturbation theory in psi

01:17:27.810 --> 01:17:30.250
lowered the energy of
the state or raised

01:17:30.250 --> 01:17:32.000
the energy of the state.

01:17:32.000 --> 01:17:35.920
So in other words, we've done
a hypothetical calculation.

01:17:35.920 --> 01:17:38.920
Hey, what would the
system feel like if there

01:17:38.920 --> 01:17:40.630
were a little bit
of superfluidity?

01:17:40.630 --> 01:17:43.730
If the system says great,
I've lowered my energy,

01:17:43.730 --> 01:17:45.970
then we know we are in
the superfluid state.

01:17:45.970 --> 01:17:48.830
When the system says no,
I raised my energy because

01:17:48.830 --> 01:17:52.090
of the psi, then the system
has rejected our idea

01:17:52.090 --> 01:17:54.120
to introduce superfluidity.

01:17:54.120 --> 01:17:56.520
So therefore, the question
we are raising now

01:17:56.520 --> 01:18:00.830
is after we have done the
calculation, for what values

01:18:00.830 --> 01:18:07.100
of U and j is it favorable
to introduce a psi or not?

01:18:07.100 --> 01:18:09.390
Now I was expecting the
question of some of you

01:18:09.390 --> 01:18:12.030
that in second-order
perturbation theory,

01:18:12.030 --> 01:18:15.690
second-order perturbation
theory always lowers the energy.

01:18:15.690 --> 01:18:18.850
But remember, this is why I
emphasized the minus sign--

01:18:18.850 --> 01:18:24.910
we had a psi squared term
which came from that, which

01:18:24.910 --> 01:18:28.450
came from the last term of the
decoupling approximation, which

01:18:28.450 --> 01:18:30.090
had a minus sign.

01:18:30.090 --> 01:18:34.120
And therefore, we
have in psi squared

01:18:34.120 --> 01:18:37.755
one term which came
from this special psi--

01:18:37.755 --> 01:18:40.530
and I emphasized in the
decoupling approximation.

01:18:40.530 --> 01:18:42.500
And we have a contribution
of psi squared

01:18:42.500 --> 01:18:44.480
which comes from
perturbation theory.

01:18:44.480 --> 01:18:49.030
And the two together can
actually change their sign.

01:18:49.030 --> 01:18:51.695
So what we have right now is
if you describe the ground

01:18:51.695 --> 01:18:55.910
state as a function of psi,
we have our unperturbed energy

01:18:55.910 --> 01:18:58.500
of the Mott insulating
states, and then we

01:18:58.500 --> 01:19:01.390
have a term in psi squared.

01:19:01.390 --> 01:19:06.620
And we should-- and we could,
but we don't-- calculate

01:19:06.620 --> 01:19:09.740
the next order in
psi to the four.

01:19:09.740 --> 01:19:12.290
And it turns out in fourth-order
perturbation theory,

01:19:12.290 --> 01:19:14.490
this term is always positive.

01:19:14.490 --> 01:19:17.300
So what happens now
to the total energy

01:19:17.300 --> 01:19:22.120
when this term A2, which we
have exactly analytically

01:19:22.120 --> 01:19:27.610
calculated-- if this term A2
is larger or smaller than 0.

01:19:27.610 --> 01:19:33.090
Well, if you have a parabolic
term and a quartic term,

01:19:33.090 --> 01:19:38.390
in this case, both the
quadratic and the quartic term

01:19:38.390 --> 01:19:40.850
are opening up
like in a U shape,

01:19:40.850 --> 01:19:44.510
but here the total energy
turns into W shape.

01:19:44.510 --> 01:19:47.240
And the interpretation
is fairly simple.

01:19:47.240 --> 01:19:49.390
Under those
conditions, the system

01:19:49.390 --> 01:19:54.010
prefers to have psi equal
0, whereas here, it's

01:19:54.010 --> 01:19:58.120
like the system wants to
have a psi parameter which

01:19:58.120 --> 01:20:00.960
is finite, either
positive or negative.

01:20:00.960 --> 01:20:03.110
And whether it's
positive or negative

01:20:03.110 --> 01:20:05.520
is sometimes called
spontaneous symmetry breaking

01:20:05.520 --> 01:20:08.190
between two
degenerate solutions.

01:20:08.190 --> 01:20:10.160
What I'm showing
here is, of course,

01:20:10.160 --> 01:20:12.680
very similar to the
Ginzburg-Landau theory

01:20:12.680 --> 01:20:15.980
of phase transitions, where
you have an effective potential

01:20:15.980 --> 01:20:19.370
and the phase transition
takes place when

01:20:19.370 --> 01:20:21.980
the second-order
coefficient changes sign,

01:20:21.980 --> 01:20:24.890
and the effective potential
turns from U-shaped

01:20:24.890 --> 01:20:27.020
into W-shaped.

01:20:27.020 --> 01:20:28.260
So that's what we have done.

01:20:31.190 --> 01:20:34.240
So anyway, I think this
is a nice problem where

01:20:34.240 --> 01:20:36.980
the interpretation
is, I think, much more

01:20:36.980 --> 01:20:39.120
subtle than the
calculation itself.

01:20:39.120 --> 01:20:42.410
But we've calculated
the phase transition.

01:20:42.410 --> 01:20:44.200
Everything is analytic.

01:20:44.200 --> 01:20:46.090
Here is the analytic
result, which

01:20:46.090 --> 01:20:48.515
I know with very
indigestible notation.

01:20:51.570 --> 01:20:56.070
I followed exactly the paper
by Vanderstraeten, [? Stouff ?]

01:20:56.070 --> 01:20:58.860
and collaborators, which
is posted on the website.

01:20:58.860 --> 01:21:02.060
You can plot this phase
diagram in this way.

01:21:02.060 --> 01:21:04.200
But if you use what
is more common,

01:21:04.200 --> 01:21:09.260
normalize the chemical potential
by U and normalize j by U,

01:21:09.260 --> 01:21:13.470
you get these wonderful
lobes of the Mott insulator

01:21:13.470 --> 01:21:15.940
where you see that,
if you increase

01:21:15.940 --> 01:21:19.790
the chemical potential, you
have N equals 1, N equals 2,

01:21:19.790 --> 01:21:23.192
N equals 3, Mott insulator,
and in between you

01:21:23.192 --> 01:21:25.530
go through superfluid regions.

01:21:25.530 --> 01:21:29.290
However if your
tunneling is larger,

01:21:29.290 --> 01:21:32.920
if your tunneling is too
large, you're only superfluid.

01:21:32.920 --> 01:21:36.330
So this is sort
of the way how you

01:21:36.330 --> 01:21:39.890
derive this rather
rich phase diagram

01:21:39.890 --> 01:21:43.190
of bosonic atoms in
an optical lattice.

01:21:43.190 --> 01:21:45.260
Green is an insulating state.

01:21:45.260 --> 01:21:49.990
And white is the
superfluid state.

01:21:49.990 --> 01:21:52.350
Let me just conclude by
showing a few slides how

01:21:52.350 --> 01:21:54.090
this can be observed.

01:21:54.090 --> 01:21:57.410
So in one case, we have
an insulating state

01:21:57.410 --> 01:22:00.410
with a definite number
of particles per site.

01:22:00.410 --> 01:22:02.680
And here we have
superfluid state,

01:22:02.680 --> 01:22:06.790
which has the normal
fluctuations in number.

01:22:10.260 --> 01:22:13.830
Here's another cartoon picture
of an condensate in the lowest

01:22:13.830 --> 01:22:15.130
Bloch wave function.

01:22:15.130 --> 01:22:19.430
And here you have
localized number states.

01:22:19.430 --> 01:22:22.810
Often, you observe the
transition by taking the system

01:22:22.810 --> 01:22:25.430
and releasing it
in time of flight

01:22:25.430 --> 01:22:27.470
into ballistic expansion.

01:22:27.470 --> 01:22:29.850
If the superfluidity
is coherent,

01:22:29.850 --> 01:22:33.760
the wave function on the
different sites is coherent.

01:22:33.760 --> 01:22:38.310
And what you get is a
multi-slit interference pattern,

01:22:38.310 --> 01:22:40.320
which is a diffraction pattern.

01:22:40.320 --> 01:22:43.830
And you see these characteristic
diffraction patterns.

01:22:43.830 --> 01:22:46.320
It's an in-slit
diffraction pattern

01:22:46.320 --> 01:22:50.360
which characterizes the
coherence in the initial state.

01:22:50.360 --> 01:22:53.870
However if you have a
completely isolating state,

01:22:53.870 --> 01:22:56.950
you have a Gaussian wave
packet on each side, which

01:22:56.950 --> 01:22:59.900
has nothing to do with
the next neighbor.

01:22:59.900 --> 01:23:02.420
And then the Gaussian
wave function simply

01:23:02.420 --> 01:23:05.550
expands in a structureless way.

01:23:05.550 --> 01:23:07.600
And so the transition
from here to there

01:23:07.600 --> 01:23:12.670
happens exactly when
the ratio of U over j

01:23:12.670 --> 01:23:14.900
crosses the value
we have derived.

01:23:17.530 --> 01:23:19.140
There's another
technique of observing

01:23:19.140 --> 01:23:21.240
that which is more recent.

01:23:21.240 --> 01:23:23.800
This is a quantum
gas microscopes

01:23:23.800 --> 01:23:26.240
where you do the same
physics in two dimensions,

01:23:26.240 --> 01:23:31.210
so you have only one plane
where this physics takes place.

01:23:31.210 --> 01:23:34.860
And you can observe atoms
now with a microscope.

01:23:34.860 --> 01:23:38.710
So each green dot
here is an atom.

01:23:38.710 --> 01:23:41.720
If you sort of zoom in.

01:23:41.720 --> 01:23:45.780
And if you now study
the region where

01:23:45.780 --> 01:23:49.050
you go through the superfluid
to the Mott insulator,

01:23:49.050 --> 01:23:56.030
you see that you have
exactly one atom per site.

01:23:56.030 --> 01:24:00.530
If you increase the atom
number, you have an insulator

01:24:00.530 --> 01:24:02.800
with one atom per site.

01:24:02.800 --> 01:24:06.450
And in the middle,
you have state

01:24:06.450 --> 01:24:08.530
with two atoms per site,
which-- for reasons

01:24:08.530 --> 01:24:11.800
I don't want to discuss-- are
color-coded here in black.

01:24:11.800 --> 01:24:14.070
And that sort of
goes on and goes on.

01:24:14.070 --> 01:24:18.430
So you can really
resolve site per site

01:24:18.430 --> 01:24:21.430
the occupation of the
number of atoms per site.

01:24:24.120 --> 01:24:27.580
So I think I'll stop
here with the Bose gases.

01:24:27.580 --> 01:24:29.440
When you think the
Mott insulator is

01:24:29.440 --> 01:24:32.410
the end of the story, all
motion has been frozen out

01:24:32.410 --> 01:24:34.920
and you have one
particle per site, well,

01:24:34.920 --> 01:24:37.170
it could be the
beginning of a new story.

01:24:37.170 --> 01:24:40.640
Because if you use two
different hyperfine states,

01:24:40.640 --> 01:24:44.640
spin up and spin down, we
can talk about spin ordering.

01:24:44.640 --> 01:24:48.410
But this would be a
whole different lecture.

